{"title_page": "Stanley Clinton-Davis, Baron Clinton-Davis", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n'''Stanley Clinton Clinton-Davis, Baron Clinton-Davis''', [[Privy Counsellor|PC]] (born 6 December 1928), born '''Stanley Clinton Davis''', is a [[Labour Party (UK)|British Labour politician]], former [[European Commissioner]], former [[Minister (government)|minister]] and [[solicitor]].  He served as [[Member of parliament|Member of Parliament (MP)]] for [[Hackney Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Hackney Central]] (1970\u20131983), and was a minister in the Labour governments of Prime Ministers [[Harold Wilson]], [[James Callaghan]] and [[Tony Blair]].  He was European Commissioner in the [[Delors Commission]] (1985\u20131989).  In 1990, he became a [[Life peer|Life Peer]] as Baron Clinton-Davis, of Hackney in the [[London Borough of Hackney]], sitting on the Labour benches in the [[House of Lords]] until his retirement in 2018. He changed his name to Stanley Clinton-Davis by [[deed poll]].<ref>''[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]]''</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nDavis was born in Hackney on 6 December 1928, the only child of Jewish parents Sidney and Lilly Davis.  He was educated at [[Hackney Downs School]], [[Mercers' School]], and [[King's College London]], where he graduated in Law in 1950. He later became a solicitor.\n\n== Early career ==\nDavis became interested in Labour politics from an early age.  He joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] at the age of 15 and formed the Labour Society at [[King's College London|King's College London]].  He was a member of the executive council of the [[Labour Students|National Association of Labour Student Organisations]] (1948\u201350).\n\nIn 1959, Davis was elected as a councillor for the [[London Borough of Hackney]].  He served as a councillor until 1971 and was Chairman of Social Services. He was Mayor of Hackney in 1968\u20131969.\n\n== House of Commons ==\nDavis first stood as [[Prospective parliamentary candidate|Parliamentary Candidate]] for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] held constituency of [[Portsmouth Langstone (UK Parliament constituency)|Portsmouth Langstone]] in the [[1955 United Kingdom general election|1955 General Election]] and for the marginal constituency of [[Great Yarmouth (UK Parliament constituency)|Yarmouth]] in the [[1959 United Kingdom general election|1959]] and [[1964 United Kingdom general election|1964]] General Elections.\n\nDavis was elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 General Election]] as MP for [[Hackney Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Hackney Central]].  He served as MP for the constituency until 1983, when the constituency was abolished due to boundary changes.\n\n=== Government ===\nDavis' first ministerial post, which he held from 1974 until 1979, was as Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Companies, Aviation and Shipping in the governments of Prime Ministers [[Harold Wilson]] and [[James Callaghan]].\n\n=== Opposition ===\nFollowing the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\u2019s victory in the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 General Election]], Davis remained on the Labour front bench as the Opposition Spokesman on Trade, Prices and Consumer Protection (1979\u201381) and Foreign Affairs (1981\u201383).\n\n== European Commission ==\nIn 1985, Davis was appointed to serve as [[European Commissioner]] alongside [[Arthur Cockfield, Baron Cockfield|Lord Cockfield]] in the [[Delors Commission]]. He was the European Commissioner for Transport, the Environment and Nuclear Safety until 1989.\n\nIn 1990, Clinton-Davis was awarded the [[Order of Leopold II|Grand Cross Order of King Leopold II of Belgium]] for services to the [[European Economic Community|European Community]].\n\nClinton-Davis was a member of the United Kingdom Delegation to the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]] and [[Assembly of the Western European Union|Western European Union]] (1999\u20132001).\n\n== House of Lords ==\nClinton-Davis was appointed to the [[House of Lords]] in May 1990.  He was Opposition Spokesman for Transport (1990\u201397) and Supporting Spokesperson for Trade and Industry (1990\u201396) and Foreign Affairs (1990\u201397).\n\nFollowing the Labour victory in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 General Election]], Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] decided to use the experience of a handful of former Labour ministers at the commencement of his [[New Labour]] project.  Clinton-Davis was appointed as [[Minister of State for Trade]], serving in the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] until 1998.\n\nClinton-Davis was appointed and sworn in as a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in 1998.\n\nHe retired from the House of Lords on 10 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-clinton-davis/1116|title=Lord Clinton-Davis|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]}}</ref>\n\n== Other offices and honorary positions ==\nClinton-Davis has held a number of senior positions, including Chairman (1989\u201396) and later President (1996\u201397) of the [[Refugee Council|British Refugee Council]]. Clinton-Davis was Chairman (1980\u201384, 1989\u20132001) and later President (2001) of the [http://www.acops.org.uk/ Advisory Committee on Protection of the Sea (ACOPS)].  He was Vice-President of the [http://www.societyoflabourlawyers.org.uk/ Society of Labour Lawyers] (1987), Vice-President of the [[Chartered Institute of Environmental Health]], Honorary Member of the Executive Council of Justice and President of the [[Local Government Association|Association of Municipal Authorities]].  Clinton-Davis was Chairman of the Packaging Standards Council (1993\u201397).\n\nFrom 1980\u20132011, Clinton-Davis was President of the [[British Airline Pilots' Association|British Airline Pilots Association (BALPA)]] and is now Honorary Life President.  He was also President of the [http://www.ukmpa.org/ UK Pilots Association (Marine)].\n\nClinton-Davis was a member (1989\u20131998) and later Chairman (1999\u20132004) of the [http://www.unep.org/sasakawa/ Sasakawa Environment Prize] Selection Committee.  The award later came under the auspices of the [[United Nations Environment Programme|United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP)]].\n\nClinton-Davis is an honorary fellow of the [[Politehnica University of Bucharest|Polytechnic University of Bucharest]], a fellow of [[King's College London|King's College London]] and an honorary fellow of [[Queen Mary University of London]].\n\n== Legal career ==\nClinton-Davis has over 50 years of service as a [[solicitor]]. He became a solicitor in November 1953 and was a founding partner of Clintons, becoming head of its Hackney branch, Clinton Davis & Co.\n\nClinton-Davis has also worked as Consultant on European Law and Affairs for [[SJ Berwin|S. J. Berwin & Co]] (1989\u201397, 1998\u20132003).\n\n== Jewish affairs ==\nClinton-Davis is a prominent advocate for the Jewish community and has spoken in Parliament on numerous occasions on issues affecting the Jewish community and Israel.  He was Vice President of the [[All-Party Parliamentary Group against Antisemitism]] and has been a supporter of [[Labour Friends of Israel]].  He was an executive member of the [[Institute of Jewish Affairs]] (1993\u201397).  He is a former director of [[The Jewish Chronicle]] and former member of the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nClinton-Davis lives in North London with his wife Frances Jane (n\u00e9e Lucas).  They married in 1954 and have four children and many grandchildren.  Clinton-Davis counts among his hobbies football, cricket and golf. He is a supporter of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal Football Club]] and [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient Football Club]].\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n*''Times Guide to the House of Commons, 1979''\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-clinton-davis | Stanley Clinton Davis }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Herbert Butler]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = Member of Parliament for [[Hackney Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Hackney Central]]\n | years  = [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970]]\u2013[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = constituency abolished }}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[European Commissioner]] for [[European Commissioner for the Environment|Environment]], [[European Commissioner for Consumer Protection|consumer protection]] and [[European Commissioner for Transport|transport]]\n  | years  = 1985\u20131988\n  | before = [[Karl-Heinz Narjes]] <small>([[European Commissioner for the Environment|environment]] & [[European Commissioner for Consumer Protection|consumer protection]])</small><br> [[Giorgios Contogeorgis]] <small>([[European Commissioner for Transport|transport]])</small>\n  | after  = [[Carlo Ripa di Meana]] <small>([[European Commissioner for the Environment|environment]])</small><br>[[Grigoris Varfis]] <small>([[European Commissioner for Consumer Protection|consumer protection]])</small> [[Karel Van Miert]] <small>([[European Commissioner for Transport|transport]])</small>\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{European Commissioners from the United Kingdom}}\n{{European Commissioner for Transport}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clinton Davis, Stanley}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:Hackney Members of Parliament|D]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers|Clinton-Davis]]\n[[Category:British European Commissioners]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hackney Downs School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Jewish British politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n'''Stanley Clinton Clinton-Davis, Baron Clinton-Davis''', [[Privy Counsellor|PC]] (born 6 December 1928), born '''Stanley Clinton Davis''', is a [[Labour Party (UK)|British Labour politician]], former [[European Commissioner]], former [[Minister (government)|minister]] and [[solicitor]].  He served as [[Member of parliament|Member of Parliament (MP)]] for [[Hackney Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Hackney Central]] (1970\u20131983), and was a minister in the Labour governments of Prime Ministers [[Harold Wilson]], [[James Callaghan]] and [[Tony Blair]].  He was European Commissioner in the [[Delors Commission]] (1985\u20131989).  In 1990, he became a [[Life peer|Life Peer]] as Baron Clinton-Davis, of Hackney in the [[London Borough of Hackney]], sitting on the Labour benches in the [[House of Lords]] until his retirement in 2018. He changed his name to Stanley Clinton-Davis by [[deed poll]].<ref>''[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]]''</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nDavis was born in Hackney on 6 December 1928, the only child of Jewish parents Sidney and Lilly Davis.  He was educated at [[Hackney Downs School]], [[Mercers' School]], and [[King's College London]], where he graduated in Law in 1950. He later became a solicitor.\n\n== Early career ==\nDavis became interested in Labour politics from an early age.  He joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] at the age of 15 and formed the Labour Society at [[King's College London|King\u2019s College London]].  He was a member of the executive council of the [[Labour Students|National Association of Labour Student Organisations]] (1948\u201350).\n\nIn 1959, Davis was elected as a councillor for the [[London Borough of Hackney]].  He served as a councillor until 1971 and was Chairman of Social Services. He was Mayor of Hackney in 1968\u20131969.\n\n== House of Commons ==\nDavis first stood as [[Prospective parliamentary candidate|Parliamentary Candidate]] for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] held constituency of [[Portsmouth Langstone (UK Parliament constituency)|Portsmouth Langstone]] in the [[1955 United Kingdom general election|1955 General Election]] and for the marginal constituency of [[Great Yarmouth (UK Parliament constituency)|Yarmouth]] in the [[1959 United Kingdom general election|1959]] and [[1964 United Kingdom general election|1964]] General Elections.\n\nDavis was elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 General Election]] as MP for [[Hackney Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Hackney Central]].  He served as MP for the constituency until 1983, when the constituency was abolished due to boundary changes.\n\n=== Government ===\nDavis' first ministerial post, which he held from 1974 until 1979, was as Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Companies, Aviation and Shipping in the governments of Prime Ministers [[Harold Wilson]] and [[James Callaghan]].\n\n=== Opposition ===\nFollowing the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\u2019s victory in the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 General Election]], Davis remained on the Labour front bench as the Opposition Spokesman on Trade, Prices and Consumer Protection (1979\u201381) and Foreign Affairs (1981\u201383).\n\n== European Commission ==\nIn 1985, Davis was appointed to serve as [[European Commissioner]] alongside [[Arthur Cockfield, Baron Cockfield|Lord Cockfield]] in the [[Delors Commission]]. He was the European Commissioner for Transport, the Environment and Nuclear Safety until 1989.\n\nIn 1990, Clinton-Davis was awarded the [[Order of Leopold II|Grand Cross Order of King Leopold II of Belgium]] for services to the [[European Economic Community|European Community]].\n\nClinton-Davis was a member of the United Kingdom Delegation to the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]] and [[Assembly of the Western European Union|Western European Union]] (1999\u20132001).\n\n== House of Lords ==\nClinton-Davis was appointed to the [[House of Lords]] in May 1990.  He was Opposition Spokesman for Transport (1990\u201397) and Supporting Spokesperson for Trade and Industry (1990\u201396) and Foreign Affairs (1990\u201397).\n\nFollowing the Labour victory in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 General Election]], Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] decided to use the experience of a handful of former Labour ministers at the commencement of his [[New Labour]] project.  Clinton-Davis was appointed as [[Minister of State for Trade]], serving in the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] until 1998.\n\nClinton-Davis was appointed and sworn in as a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in 1998.\n\nHe retired from the House of Lords on 10 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-clinton-davis/1116|title=Lord Clinton-Davis|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]}}</ref>\n\n== Other offices and honorary positions ==\nClinton-Davis has held a number of senior positions, including Chairman (1989\u201396) and later President (1996\u201397) of the [[Refugee Council|British Refugee Council]]. Clinton-Davis was Chairman (1980\u201384, 1989\u20132001) and later President (2001) of the [http://www.acops.org.uk/ Advisory Committee on Protection of the Sea (ACOPS)].  He was Vice-President of the [http://www.societyoflabourlawyers.org.uk/ Society of Labour Lawyers] (1987), Vice-President of the [[Chartered Institute of Environmental Health]], Honorary Member of the Executive Council of Justice and President of the [[Local Government Association|Association of Municipal Authorities]].  Clinton-Davis was Chairman of the Packaging Standards Council (1993\u201397).\n\nFrom 1980\u20132011, Clinton-Davis was President of the [[British Airline Pilots' Association|British Airline Pilots Association (BALPA)]] and is now Honorary Life President.  He was also President of the [http://www.ukmpa.org/ UK Pilots Association (Marine)].\n\nClinton-Davis was a member (1989\u20131998) and later Chairman (1999\u20132004) of the [http://www.unep.org/sasakawa/ Sasakawa Environment Prize] Selection Committee.  The award later came under the auspices of the [[United Nations Environment Programme|United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP)]].\n\nClinton-Davis is an honorary fellow of the [[Politehnica University of Bucharest|Polytechnic University of Bucharest]], a fellow of [[King's College London|King\u2019s College London]] and an honorary fellow of [[Queen Mary University of London]].\n\n== Legal career ==\nClinton-Davis has over 50 years of service as a [[solicitor]]. He became a solicitor in November 1953 and was a founding partner of Clintons, becoming head of its Hackney branch, Clinton Davis & Co.\n\nClinton-Davis has also worked as Consultant on European Law and Affairs for [[SJ Berwin|S. J. Berwin & Co]] (1989\u201397, 1998\u20132003).\n\n== Jewish affairs ==\nClinton-Davis is a prominent advocate for the Jewish community and has spoken in Parliament on numerous occasions on issues affecting the Jewish community and Israel.  He was Vice President of the [[All-Party Parliamentary Group against Antisemitism]] and has been a supporter of [[Labour Friends of Israel]].  He was an executive member of the [[Institute of Jewish Affairs]] (1993\u201397).  He is a former director of [[The Jewish Chronicle]] and former member of the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nClinton-Davis lives in North London with his wife Frances Jane (n\u00e9e Lucas).  They married in 1954 and have four children and many grandchildren.  Clinton-Davis counts among his hobbies football, cricket and golf. He is a supporter of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal Football Club]] and [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient Football Club]].\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n*''Times Guide to the House of Commons, 1979''\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-clinton-davis | Stanley Clinton Davis }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Herbert Butler]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = Member of Parliament for [[Hackney Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Hackney Central]]\n | years  = [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970]]\u2013[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = constituency abolished }}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[European Commissioner]] for [[European Commissioner for the Environment|Environment]], [[European Commissioner for Consumer Protection|consumer protection]] and [[European Commissioner for Transport|transport]]\n  | years  = 1985\u20131988\n  | before = [[Karl-Heinz Narjes]] <small>([[European Commissioner for the Environment|environment]] & [[European Commissioner for Consumer Protection|consumer protection]])</small><br> [[Giorgios Contogeorgis]] <small>([[European Commissioner for Transport|transport]])</small>\n  | after  = [[Carlo Ripa di Meana]] <small>([[European Commissioner for the Environment|environment]])</small><br>[[Grigoris Varfis]] <small>([[European Commissioner for Consumer Protection|consumer protection]])</small> [[Karel Van Miert]] <small>([[European Commissioner for Transport|transport]])</small>\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{European Commissioners from the United Kingdom}}\n{{European Commissioner for Transport}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clinton Davis, Stanley}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:Hackney Members of Parliament|D]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers|Clinton-Davis]]\n[[Category:British European Commissioners]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hackney Downs School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Jewish British politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stanley_Clinton-Davis,_Baron_Clinton-Davis"}
{"title_page": "Sydney Chapman (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name         = Sir Sydney Chapman \n|honorific-suffix = \n|image        = Sydney Chapman MP.jpg\n|office       = [[Vice-Chamberlain of the Household]]\n|primeminister= [[John Major]]\n|1blankname   = [[Lord Chamberlain|Lord Cham.]]\n|1namedata    = [[David Ogilvy, 13th Earl of Airlie|The Earl of Airlie]]\n|term_start   = 15 April 1992\n|term_end     = 7 July 1995\n|predecessor  = [[John Taylor (Solihull MP)|John Taylor]]\n|successor    = [[Timothy Kirkhope]]\n|office2      = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)|Chipping Barnet]]\n|term_start2  = 5 May 1979\n|term_end2    = 11 April 2005\n|predecessor2 = [[Reginald Maudling]]\n|successor2   = [[Theresa Villiers]]\n|constituency_MP3 = [[Birmingham Handsworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Handsworth]]\n|term_start3  = 18 June 1970\n|term_end3    = 8 February 1974\n|predecessor3 = [[Edward Boyle, Baron Boyle of Handsworth|Edward Boyle]]\n|successor3   = [[John Lee (Labour politician)|John Lee]]\n|birth_name   = Sydney Brookes Chapman\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1935|10|17|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[Macclesfield]], England\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|2014|10|09|1935|10|17|df=yes}}\n|death_place  = [[Lower Heyford]], England\n|nationality  = British\n|party        = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Claire McNab<br />|1976|1987}}<br />{{marriage|Teresa Munoz<br />|2005}}\n|children     = 3\n|education    = [[Rugby School]]\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Manchester]]\n|profession   = [[Architecture]]\n}}\n'''Sir Sydney Brookes Chapman''' (17 October 1935 \u2013 9 October 2014) was a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician and architect who served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Birmingham Handsworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Handsworth]] and [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)|Chipping Barnet]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sir Sydney Chapman - obituary|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/11213493/Sir-Sydney-Chapman-obituary.html|website =The Daily Telegraph|accessdate = 2015-12-28}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nChapman was educated at [[Rugby School]] and [[Manchester University]], where he studied architecture, gaining his Diploma in 1958 and [[ARIBA]] in 1960.  He was Chairman of the [[Young Conservatives (UK)|Young Conservatives]] from 1964 to 1966.<ref name=Burkes>[[Burke's Peerage]], accessed 1 August 2009</ref>\n\nHe married his first wife, Claire in 1976 (she was also his secretary when he was an MP), and they had three children.<ref name=Barnet>[http://www.barnet4u.co.uk/Index/Main%20Page%20links/Barnet%20Blogs/whoswho.html Who's Who in Barnet]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2005, he married his second wife, Teresa at Chelsea Town Hall.\n\nAfter his retirement from politics, he moved from Barnet to Oxfordshire.{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}\nHe was a vice-chairman of the [[Council of Christians and Jews]]<ref name=CCJ>[http://www.ccj.org.uk/Presidents.html Council of Christians and Jews] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090709092912/http://www.ccj.org.uk/Presidents.html |date=9 July 2009 }} website accessed 10 April 2012</ref> and on the Council of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] for 2009\u20132012.<ref name=RIBA>[http://www.builderandengineer.co.uk/news/general/riba-council-election-results-2009-4201.html Builder and Engineer online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911110145/http://www.builderandengineer.co.uk/news/general/riba-council-election-results-2009-4201.html |date=11 September 2011 }} RIBA Council Election Results 2009</ref>\n\nSir Sydney died on 9 October 2014 in Oxfordshire.<ref name=BarnetToday>[http://www.barnet-today.co.uk/News.cfm?id=10933&headline=Former%20Chipping%20Barnet%20MP%20Sir%20Sydney%20Chapman%20dies Barnet Today 10 Oct 2014] Former Chipping Barnet MP Sir Sydney Chapman dies</ref> A Service of Thanksgiving was organised by his family on 10 June 2015 at [[St Margaret's, Westminster|St Margaret's Church]], [[Westminster]]. Attended by some 400 people including family, former colleagues, friends and constituents, the eulogies were read by Lord Ryder, Philip Porter and Sydney's sister, Cllr Christine Bateson.{{citation needed|date= February 2017}}\n\n==Political career==\nChapman first stood for Parliament, unsuccessfully, at [[Stalybridge and Hyde (UK Parliament constituency)|Stalybridge and Hyde]] at the [[1964 United Kingdom general election|1964 election]], but was defeated by the incumbent [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Fred Blackburn]].\n\nHe was first elected to Parliament in 1970 as MP for [[Birmingham Handsworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Handsworth]], but lost his seat when Labour returned to power at the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]].  During this period he was notable for ''[[Plant A Tree In '73]]'', an initiative which had the support of [[Edward Heath]]'s government and led to the formation of [[The Tree Council]].<ref name=DT05>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1487222/Father-of-the-House-heads-list-of-MPs-about-to-bow-out.html Daily Telegraph] 6 April 2005</ref><ref name=Hansard2005>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo050606/debtext/50606-25.htm Hansard] 6 June 2005</ref> In the ''Plant A Tree'' role, Chapman had to work closely with the newly-formed [[Secretary of State for the Environment|Department of the Environment]], only to discover that the senior official concerned had been a prefect at Rugby at whom he had once thrown a [[stink bomb]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nFive years later, at the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 election]], Chapman was returned as MP for [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)|Chipping Barnet]].  He was briefly a [[whip (politics)|whip]] during [[John Major]]'s administration, one of his principal tasks being to provide Queen [[Elizabeth II]] with daily reports of Parliamentary proceedings. His conscientious attention to this role led to his being knighted. Chapman was a member of the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]] from 1997 to 2005.<ref name=COE>[http://assembly.coe.int/ASP/AssemblyList/AL_MemberDetails.asp?MemberID=3841 Council of Europe] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123172458/http://assembly.coe.int/ASP/AssemblyList/AL_MemberDetails.asp?MemberID=3841 |date=23 January 2010 }} Sir Sydney Chapman</ref>\n\n==Local achievements==\nIn the late 1980s, following the death of a horse rider crossing the [[A1 in London|A1]] trunk road in [[Arkley]], Sir Sydney championed the campaign to have a bridge put in for walkers, riders and cyclists' use.  This campaign was successful, and the bridge opened in 1991. In recognition of his work, he was presented with an award by the [[British Horse Society]]'s President at the bridge's official opening ceremony.<ref>Barnet and Whetstone Independent, 9 January 1992</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Sydney Chapman (2010) ''Back to the Drawing Board - Memoirs of a Back Bencher'' (Absolute) {{ISBN|0955213991}}  Autobiography\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | sir-sydney-chapman | Sir Sydney Chapman }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060908171251/http://www.sherlock-holmes.org.uk/galleries/annual2006/pages/Sir%20Sydney%20Chapman_jpg.htm Sir Sydney Chapman] Photograph, 2006\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Birmingham Handsworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Handsworth]]\n  | years  = 1970\u20131974\n  | before = [[Edward Boyle, Baron Boyle of Handsworth|Edward Boyle]]\n  | after  = [[John Lee (Labour politician)|John Lee]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)|Chipping Barnet]]\n  | years  = 1979\u20132005\n  | before = [[Reginald Maudling]]\n  | after  = [[Theresa Villiers]]\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Vice-Chamberlain of the Household]]\n  | years  = 1992\u20131995\n  | before = [[John Taylor (Solihull MP)|John Taylor]]\n  | after  = [[Timothy Kirkhope]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chapman, Sydney}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rugby School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Architects from Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name         = Sir Sydney Chapman \n|honorific-suffix = \n|image        = Sydney Chapman MP.jpg\n|office       = [[Vice-Chamberlain of the Household]]\n|primeminister= [[John Major]]\n|1blankname   = [[Lord Chamberlain|Lord Cham.]]\n|1namedata    = [[David Ogilvy, 13th Earl of Airlie|The Earl of Airlie]]\n|term_start   = 15 April 1992\n|term_end     = 7 July 1995\n|predecessor  = [[John Taylor (Solihull MP)|John Taylor]]\n|successor    = [[Timothy Kirkhope]]\n|office2      = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)|Chipping Barnet]]\n|term_start2  = 5 May 1979\n|term_end2    = 11 April 2005\n|predecessor2 = [[Reginald Maudling]]\n|successor2   = [[Theresa Villiers]]\n|constituency_MP3 = [[Birmingham Handsworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Handsworth]]\n|term_start3  = 18 June 1970\n|term_end3    = 8 February 1974\n|predecessor3 = [[Edward Boyle, Baron Boyle of Handsworth|Edward Boyle]]\n|successor3   = [[John Lee (Labour politician)|John Lee]]\n|birth_name   = Sydney Brookes Chapman\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1935|10|17|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[Macclesfield]], England\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|2014|10|09|1935|10|17|df=yes}}\n|death_place  = [[Lower Heyford]], England\n|nationality  = British\n|party        = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Claire McNab<br />|1976|1987}}<br />{{marriage|Teresa Munoz<br />|2005}}\n|children     = 3\n|education    = [[Rugby School]]\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Manchester]]\n|profession   = [[Architecture]]\n}}\n'''Sir Sydney Brookes Chapman''' (17 October 1935 \u2013 9 October 2014) was a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician and architect who served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Birmingham Handsworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Handsworth]] and [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)|Chipping Barnet]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sir Sydney Chapman - obituary|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/11213493/Sir-Sydney-Chapman-obituary.html|website =The Daily Telegraph|accessdate = 2015-12-28}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nChapman was educated at [[Rugby School]] and [[Manchester University]], where he studied architecture, gaining his Diploma in 1958 and [[ARIBA]] in 1960.  He was Chairman of the [[Young Conservatives (UK)|Young Conservatives]] from 1964 to 1966.<ref name=Burkes>[[Burke's Peerage]], accessed 1 August 2009</ref>\n\nHe married his first wife, Claire in 1976 (she was also his secretary when he was an MP), and they had three children.<ref name=Barnet>[http://www.barnet4u.co.uk/Index/Main%20Page%20links/Barnet%20Blogs/whoswho.html Who's Who in Barnet]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2005, he married his second wife, Teresa at Chelsea Town Hall.\n\nAfter his retirement from politics, he moved from Barnet to Oxfordshire.{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}\nHe was a vice-chairman of the [[Council of Christians and Jews]]<ref name=CCJ>[http://www.ccj.org.uk/Presidents.html Council of Christians and Jews] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090709092912/http://www.ccj.org.uk/Presidents.html |date=9 July 2009 }} website accessed 10 April 2012</ref> and on the Council of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] for 2009-2012.<ref name=RIBA>[http://www.builderandengineer.co.uk/news/general/riba-council-election-results-2009-4201.html Builder and Engineer online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911110145/http://www.builderandengineer.co.uk/news/general/riba-council-election-results-2009-4201.html |date=11 September 2011 }} RIBA Council Election Results 2009</ref>\n\nSir Sydney died on 9 October 2014 in Oxfordshire.<ref name=BarnetToday>[http://www.barnet-today.co.uk/News.cfm?id=10933&headline=Former%20Chipping%20Barnet%20MP%20Sir%20Sydney%20Chapman%20dies Barnet Today 10 Oct 2014] Former Chipping Barnet MP Sir Sydney Chapman dies</ref> A Service of Thanksgiving was organised by his family on 10 June 2015 at [[St Margaret's, Westminster|St Margaret's Church]], [[Westminster]]. Attended by some 400 people including family, former colleagues, friends and constituents, the eulogies were read by Lord Ryder, Philip Porter and Sydney's sister, Cllr Christine Bateson.{{citation needed|date= February 2017}}\n\n==Political career==\nChapman first stood for Parliament, unsuccessfully, at [[Stalybridge and Hyde (UK Parliament constituency)|Stalybridge and Hyde]] at the [[1964 United Kingdom general election|1964 election]], but was defeated by the incumbent [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Fred Blackburn]].\n\nHe was first elected to Parliament in 1970 as MP for [[Birmingham Handsworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Handsworth]], but lost his seat when Labour returned to power at the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]].  During this period he was notable for ''[[Plant A Tree In '73]]'', an initiative which had the support of [[Edward Heath]]'s government and led to the formation of [[The Tree Council]].<ref name=DT05>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1487222/Father-of-the-House-heads-list-of-MPs-about-to-bow-out.html Daily Telegraph] 6 April 2005</ref><ref name=Hansard2005>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo050606/debtext/50606-25.htm Hansard] 6 June 2005</ref> In the ''Plant A Tree'' role, Chapman had to work closely with the newly-formed [[Secretary of State for the Environment|Department of the Environment]], only to discover that the senior official concerned had been a prefect at Rugby at whom he had once thrown a [[stink bomb]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nFive years later, at the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 election]], Chapman was returned as MP for [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)|Chipping Barnet]].  He was briefly a [[whip (politics)|whip]] during [[John Major]]'s administration, one of his principal tasks being to provide Queen [[Elizabeth II]] with daily reports of Parliamentary proceedings. His conscientious attention to this role led to his being knighted. Chapman was a member of the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]] from 1997 to 2005.<ref name=COE>[http://assembly.coe.int/ASP/AssemblyList/AL_MemberDetails.asp?MemberID=3841 Council of Europe] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123172458/http://assembly.coe.int/ASP/AssemblyList/AL_MemberDetails.asp?MemberID=3841 |date=23 January 2010 }} Sir Sydney Chapman</ref>\n\n==Local achievements==\nIn the late 1980s, following the death of a horse rider crossing the [[A1 in London|A1]] trunk road in [[Arkley]], Sir Sydney championed the campaign to have a bridge put in for walkers, riders and cyclists' use.  This campaign was successful, and the bridge opened in 1991. In recognition of his work, he was presented with an award by the [[British Horse Society]]'s President at the bridge's official opening ceremony.<ref>Barnet and Whetstone Independent, 9 January 1992</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Sydney Chapman (2010) ''Back to the Drawing Board - Memoirs of a Back Bencher'' (Absolute) {{ISBN|0955213991}}  Autobiography\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | sir-sydney-chapman | Sir Sydney Chapman }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060908171251/http://www.sherlock-holmes.org.uk/galleries/annual2006/pages/Sir%20Sydney%20Chapman_jpg.htm Sir Sydney Chapman] Photograph, 2006\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Birmingham Handsworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Handsworth]]\n  | years  = 1970\u20131974\n  | before = [[Edward Boyle, Baron Boyle of Handsworth|Edward Boyle]]\n  | after  = [[John Lee (Labour politician)|John Lee]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Chipping Barnet (UK Parliament constituency)|Chipping Barnet]]\n  | years  = 1979\u20132005\n  | before = [[Reginald Maudling]]\n  | after  = [[Theresa Villiers]]\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Vice-Chamberlain of the Household]]\n  | years  = 1992\u20131995\n  | before = [[John Taylor (Solihull MP)|John Taylor]]\n  | after  = [[Timothy Kirkhope]]\n}}\n{{s