''[[USS Franklin D. Roosevelt (CV-42)|USS Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n*\"Fraser Blade\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Fraser (DDH 233)|HMCS ''Fraser'']]'''\n*\"Freddy\" \u2013 ''' [[HMCS Fredericton (FFH 337)|HMCS ''Fredericton'']]'''\n*\"Fleet Starship\" \u2013 '''USS ''Enterprise'' (CVN-65)'''\n*\"The Furry Wet Mound\" \u2013 '''USS ''Harry W. Hill'' (DD-986)''', humorous malapropism\n\n==G==\n*\"Galloping Ghost of the Java Coast\" \u2013 '''[[USS Houston (CA-30)|USS ''Houston'']]'''\n* \"George's Legs\" or \"Gorgeous Legs\" \u2013 French light cruiser '''Georges Leygues ''' \n*\"Germanclown\" \u2013 USS ''Germantown'' (LSD-42)\n*\"Ghetto\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Gato}}'''\n*\"Gipper\" \u2013 '''[[USS Ronald Reagan (CVN-76)|USS ''Ronald Reagan'']]'''; named for [[Ronald Reagan]]'s nickname, from his role of [[George Gipp|George \"The Gipper\" Gipp]] in the film [[Knute Rockne, All American]].\n*\"Gin Palace\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Agincourt (1913)|HMS ''Agincourt'']]'''; originally built for Brazilian Navy and given higher standards of comfort for officers, and lesser standards of comfort for the crew than most RN ships. Also a deliberate misspelling of the name: ''A Gin Court''.\n*\"The Gold Eagle\" \u2013 '''[[USS Carl Vinson (CVN-70)|USS ''Carl Vinson'']]'''\n*\"The Golden Devil\" ([[Dutch language|Dutch]] ''\"Den Gulden Duvel\"'') \u2013 '''[[HMS Sovereign of the Seas|HMS ''Sovereign of the Seas'']]'''\n*\"The Golden Guad\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Guadalcanal|LPH-7}}'''\n*''\"Le Grand Hotel\"'' \u2013 '''[[French ironclad Hoche|French Ironclad ''Hoche'']]'''\n*\"The Grand Old Lady\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Warspite (03)|HMS ''Warspite'']]'''<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/ww2peopleswar/stories/99/a4464399.shtml]</ref>\n*\u201dThe Galloping Ghost\u201d \u2013 '''[[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|USS ''Enterprise'' (CV-6)]]'''\n*\"The Gray Ghost\" \u2013 '''[[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|USS ''Enterprise'' (CV-6)]]'''\n*\"The Gray Lady\" \u2013 '''[[USS Lexington (CV-2)|USS ''Lexington'']]'''\n*\"The Gray Ghost\" - '''[[USS Iowa (BB-61)|USS ''Iowa'' (BB-61)]]'''\n*\"Grey Ghost\" \u2013 '''[[USS Pensacola (CA-24)|USS ''Pensacola'']]'''; nickname given by [[Tokyo Rose]]\n*\"Greenpig\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Greenling}}'''\n*\"GW\" \u2013 '''[[USS George Washington (CVN-73)|USS ''George Washington'']]'''; initials of the ship's namesake\n\n==H==\n*\"The Ham\" \u2013 {{USS|Ingraham|FFG-61|6}}\n*\"Happy Valley\" \u2013 '''[[USS Valley Forge (CVA-45)|USS ''Valley Forge'']]'''\n*\"He-Cat\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Hecate|HMS ''Hecate'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"HMAS Can Opener\" \u2013 '''{{HMAS|Melbourne|R21|6}}'''; given by US Navy sailors for the ship's part in the sinking of the US Navy destroyer {{USS|Frank E. Evans||6}}. ''Melbourne'' previously sank another destroyer, {{HMAS|Voyager|D04|6}}, in a similar collision.\n*\"HMS Me\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Queen Elizabeth|R08|6}}'''; from a cake presented to [[Elizabeth II]] during her first visit to the ship.<ref>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5155401/Lizzie-meet-Big-Lizzie-Majesty-steps-aboard-ship.html</ref>\n*\"HMS Refit\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Renown|1916|6}}''';\n*\"HMS Repair\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Repulse (1916)|HMS ''Repulse'']]'''\n*\"Hiroshima\" \u2013 '''[[Soviet submarine K-19|Soviet submarine ''K-19'']]''', due to a nuclear accident onboard\n*\"Hockey Puck \u2013 '''{{USS|Haleakala|AE-25}}'''; humorous malapropism \n*\"Holiday Express\" \u2013 '''[[USS Bunker Hill (CV-17)|USS ''Bunker Hill'']]'''\n*\"Holiday Inn\" \u2013 '''[[USS Bunker Hill (CV-17)|USS ''Bunker Hill'']]'''\n*\"HST\" \u2013 '''[[USS Harry S. Truman (CVN-75)|USS ''Harry S. Truman'']]'''; initials of the ship's namesake [[Harry S. Truman]]\n*\"Hairy Ass\" \u2013 '''[[USS Harry S. Truman (CVN-75)|USS ''Harry S. Truman'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Hymi G\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Hyman G. Rickover|SSN-709|6}}'''\n*\"Happy Harry\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Harry W. Hill|DD-986}}'''\n*\"Hotel Yamato\" \u2013 '''[[Japanese battleship Yamato|Japanese battleship ''Yamato'']]'''; due to the amount of time spent at Truk between August 1942 and May 1943\n\n==I==\n*\"Ike\" \u2013 '''[[USS Dwight D. Eisenhower (CVN-69)|USS ''Dwight D. Eisenhower'']]'''; based on nickname of namesake, [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]]\n*\"Ikeatraz\" \u2013 '''[[USS Dwight D. Eisenhower (CVN-69)|USS ''Dwight D. Eisenhower'']]'''; derogatory nickname given to those that served on board and had gotten in trouble in some way.\n*\"Indy\" \u2013 '''[[USS Independence (CV-62)|USS ''Independence'']]'''\n*\"Iron Duck\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Iron Duke|HMS ''Iron Duke'']]'''\n*\"Fighting I\" \u2013 '''[[USS Intrepid (CV-11)|USS ''Intrepid'']]'''\n*\"Ichiban Benjo Maru\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Ajax|AR-6}}'''; due to an outbreak of bacillary dysentery that required quarantine\n*\"Iron Woman\" {{USS|Cabot|CV-16|6}}\n\n==J==\n*\"Jimmy K\" \u2013 '''[[USS James K. Polk (SSBN-645)|USS ''James K. Polk'']]'''\n*\"Johnny Reb\" \u2013 '''[[USS John C. Stennis (CVN-74)|USS ''John C. Stennis'']]'''\n\n==K==\n*\"Kaarnavene\" \u2013 [[Finnish Navy]] '''[[Nuoli class fast gunboat]]s'''. The name means literally \"bark boat\": they were made from non-magnetic mahogany.\n*\"Kami-ha-ha\" \u2013 '''[[USS Kamehameha (SSBN-642)|USS ''Kamehameha'']]''';  humorous malapropism\n*\"King of Tomahawks\" \u2013 '''[[USS John Young (DD-973)|USS ''John Young'']]'''; probably after the ship's [[BGM-109 Tomahawk]] weapons system, or  \"The John Bone\" humorous malapropisms\n*\"Shitty Kitty\" \u2013 '''[[USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63)|USS ''Kitty Hawk'']]''';  humorous malapropism<ref name=\"seattlest\">{{cite web\n  | last = Prohaska\n  | first = Kim\n  | title = The USS Shitty Kitty Decommissioned\n  | work = Seattlest Daily\n  | date = 2009-05-14\n  | url = http://seattlest.com/2009/05/14/the_uss_shitty_kitty_decommissioned.php\n  | accessdate = 2010-10-16\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111001135314/http://seattlest.com/2009/05/14/the_uss_shitty_kitty_decommissioned.php\n  | archive-date = 2011-10-01\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref>\n*\"Knockwood\" \u2013 '''[[USS Lockwood (FF-1064)|USS ''Lockwood'']]'''\n\n==L==\n*\"Lady Lex\" \u2013 '''[[USS Lexington (CV-2)|USS ''Lexington'']]'''\n*\"Lady Lou\" \u2013 '''[[USS Louisville (CA-28)|USS ''Louisville'']]'''\n*\"Long Delayed\" \u2013 '''[[HMAS Adelaide (1918)|HMAS ''Adelaide'']]'''; rhyming play on ship's name. Fitting out and completion of the ship were delayed (almost 3 years) due to the loss of important machinery parts, as a result of enemy action, which gave rise to the nickname.\n*\"The Lord's Own\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Vengeance (1899)|HMS ''Vengeance'']]'''; derived from the phrase \"The Lord's own vengeance\", based on the sentiment of [[Epistle to the Romans|Romans]]<ref>[http://www.zianet.com/maxey/Roman24.htm 12:19]</ref>\n*\"Lost and Confused\" \u2013 '''[[USS Lewis and Clark (SSBN-644)|USS ''Lewis and Clark'']]'''\n*\"Lucky A\"  \u2013 '''[[USS Alabama (BB-60)|USS ''Alabama]]'''\n*\"Lucky E\"  \u2013 '''[[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|USS ''Enterprise]]'''\n*\"Lucky 26\" \u2013 '''[[HNoMS Stord (G26)|HNoMS ''Stord'']]'''\n*\"Lusty\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Illustrious (R06)|HMS ''Illustrious]]'''''\n*\"Lucky Number 7\" \u2013 '''[[USNS Rainier (T-AOE-7)|USS ''Rainier'']]''' \u2013 The hull number.\n\n==M==\n*\"Maggie\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Magnificent (1894)|HMS ''Magnificent'']]'''; '''[[HMCS Magnificent (CVL 21)|HMCS ''Magnificent'']]'''\n*\"The Mighty Hood\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Hood|51|6}}'''\n*\"Mighty O\" \u2013 '''[[USS Oriskany (CV-34)|USS ''Oriskany'']]'''\n*\"Mighty T\" \u2013 '''[[USS Texas (BB-35)|USS ''Texas (BB-35)'']]'''\n*\"Mighty Y\" \u2013 '''[[USS Yakutat (AVP-32)|USCGC ''Yakutat'']]'''\n*\"Mighty Mo\" \u2013 '''[[USS Missouri (BB-63)|USS ''Missouri'']]'''\n*\"Mighty Moo\" \u2013 '''[[USS Cowpens (CVL-25)|USS ''Cowpens'']]'''\n*\"Mobile Chernobyl\" \u2013 '''[[USS Enterprise (CVN-65)|USS ''Enterprise]]'''\n*\"Moskvitch\" \u2013 [[Finnish navy]] '''[[Tuima class missile boat]]s'''. Soviet-built [[Moskvitch]] cars had notoriously poor reputation in Finland.\n* \"Motel 6\" \u2013 '''USS ''Bonhomme Richard'' (LHD-6)'''\n* \"Midway Magic\" \u2013 '''USS ''Midway'' (CV-41)'''\n\n==N==\n*\"Nasty Asty\" \u2013 '''[[USS Astoria (CA-34)|USS ''Astoria'']]''' \n*\"Nasty Nick\" \u2013 '''[[USS Nicholas (FFG-47)|USS ''Nicholas'']]''', name given by crew due to the proclivity of the ship's AC units to break down in hot weather.\n*\"Nelly\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Nelson|28|6}}''' \u2013 also \"Nelsol\" \u2013 from fleet oilers with names ending in 'ol' that the Nelson class looked similar to in silhouette. \n*\"Niffy Jane\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Iphigenia|HMS ''Iphigenia'']]'''\n*\"NO Boat\" \u2013 '''[[USS New Orleans (CA-32)|USS ''New Orleans'']]'''\n*\"Northo\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Northumberland (1865)|HMS ''Northumberland'']]'''\n\n==O==\n*\"O'Broken\" \u2013 '''[[USS O'Brien (DD-975)|USS ''O'Brien'']]'''\n*\"The O-Boat\" \u2013 '''[[USS Oriskany (CV-34)|USS ''Oriskany'']]'''\n*\"Old Bones\" \u2013 '''[[HIJMS Kongo|Japanese battleship ''Kong\u014d'']]'''\n*\"Old Falling Apart\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Pennsylvania|BB-38}}''', from firing so many rounds during the bombardment of Guam, she appeared to be falling apart.\n*\"Old Formy\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Formidable (67)|HMS ''Formidable'']]'''\n*\"Old Hoodoo\" \u2013 '''[[USS Texas (1892)|USS ''Texas (1892)'']]'''\n*\"Old Mary\" \u2013 '''[[USS Maryland (BB-46)|USS ''Maryland (BB-46)'']]'''\n*\"The Old Grey Ghost of the Borneo Coast\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Albion (R07)|HMS ''Albion'']]'''<ref>http://www.hmsalbion.org.uk/{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*\"Old Ironsides\" \u2013 '''[[USS Constitution|USS ''Constitution'']]'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussconstitution.navy.mil/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070213180914/http://www.ussconstitution.navy.mil/ |archivedate=2007-02-13 }}</ref>\n*\"The Old Lady\" \u2013  '''[[HMS Warspite (03)|HMS ''Warspite'']]''', from a comment by [[Andrew Cunningham, 1st Viscount Cunningham of Hyndhope|Viscount Cunningham]];<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.postalheritage.org.uk/exhibitions/ww2stamps/cunningham |title=The British Postal Museum & Archive - Viscount Cunningham & HMS Warspite<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2006-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060822083953/http://www.postalheritage.org.uk/exhibitions/ww2stamps/cunningham |archive-date=2006-08-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> impressed by the vintage ship's speed during a mission to aid the British Army in Sicily, Cunningham remarked, \"When the old lady lifts her skirts she can run.\"<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/ww2peopleswar/stories/08/a4134908.shtml BBC - WW2 People's War - My Life My War - Chapter 12c<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*\"Old Lady of the Sea\" \u2013 '''[[USS New York (BB-34)|USS ''New York (BB-34)'']]'''\n*\"Old Salt\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Nimitz|CVN-68|6}}'''\n*\"One-Eye\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Polyphemus (1881)|HMS ''Polyphemus'']]'''; [[Polyphemus]] was a [[cyclops]] in [[Greek mythology]]\n*\"Orjalaiva Kurjala\" \u2013 [[Finnish Navy]] corvette '''[[Turunmaa class gunboat|Karjala]]'''. The word ''orjalaiva'' means [[slave ship]] in Finnish, while ''Kurjala'' references the Finnish word ''kurja'' (\"miserable\").\n*\"Outrageous\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Courageous (50)|HMS ''Courageous'']]''';<ref>[http://www.royal-navy.org/shiplist/index.php?option=com_content&task=section&id=5&Itemid=13]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }},</ref> humorous [[malapropism]]\n*\"The Oki Boat\" \u2013 '''[[USS Okinawa (LPH-3)|USS ''Okinawa'']]'''\n\n==P==\n*\"Pepper Pot\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Penelope|97|6}}''' \u2013 while docked in Valletta harbour, during the [[Siege of Malta (World War II)|Siege of Malta]], she was bombed so much she resembled a pepper pot\n*\"Pierwolf\" \u2013 '''[[USS Seawolf (SSN-575)|USS ''Seawolf'']]'''\n*\"The Pool\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Liverpool (C11)|HMS ''Liverpool'']]'''\n*\"Proud Pete\" \u2013 '''[[USS Peterson (DD-969)|USS ''Peterson'']]''';  play on \"Pete\" as a diminutive of \"Peterson\", and on the ship's [[motto]], \"Proud Tradition\"\n*\"Prune Barge\" \u2013 '''[[USS California (BB-44)|USS ''California'']]<ref>http://ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/ships/logs/BB/bb44-schaffran.html</ref>\n*\"Puffington\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Effingham (D98)|HMS ''Effingham'']]'''\n*\"Puuhamaa\" \u2013 Finnish navy [[minelayer]] '''[[Finnish minelayer Pohjanmaa|Pohjanmaa]]'''. An ironical remark of [[Puuhamaa]] amusement park.\n*\"Sweet Pea\" \u2013 '''[[USS Portland (CA-33)|USS ''Portland'']]'''\n*\"Pig Boat\" - '''[[USS California (CGN-36)|USS ''California'']]'''; The resemblance of the bear on the ship's badge to that of a pig.\n\n==Q==\n \n*\"Queerfish\" \u2013 '''[[USS Queenfish (SS-393)|USS ''Queenfish'']]'''\n*\"Quiet Warrior\" \u2013 '''[[USS Spruance (DD-963)|USS ''Spruance'']]'''\n\n==R==\n*\"The Red-Eye\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Huron (DDG 281)|HMCS ''Huron'' (DDG 281)]]''' (decommissioned); so named for the tobacco flower blossom on the ship's badge.\n*\"Refit\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Renown|1916|6}}'''\n*\"Repair\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Repulse (1916)|HMS ''Repulse'']]'''\n*\"Rezzo\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Resolution (09)|HMS ''Resolution'']]'''\n*\"Rosie\" \u2013 '''[[USS Franklin D. Roosevelt (CV-42)|USS Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n*\"Rough Rider\" \u2013 '''[[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'']]'''\n*\"Rodnol\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Rodney (29)|HMS ''Rodney'']]''' \u2013 from fleet oilers with names ending in 'ol'\n*\"Ruosteensilm\u00e4\" \u2013 [[Finnish Navy]] '''[[Finnish minelayer Ruotsinsalmi|minelayer Ruotsinsalmi]]'''. The name means ''Rusty Eye'' in Finnish.\n*\"Rusty-guts\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Restigouche (DDE 257)|HMCS ''Restigouche'']]'''<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/ArticleNews/TPStory/LAC/20051105/OBPIERS05/TPObituaries/?pageRequested=all]</ref>\n*\"Rusty W\" \u2013 '''[[USS Washington (BB-56)|USS ''Washington'']]'''\n\n==S==\n*\"Sara\", \"Super Sara\", \"Sorry Sara\", \"Sister Sara\", \"Stripe-Stack Sara\", \"Sinking Sara\" or \"Sara Maru\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Saratoga|CV-3|6}}'''\n*\"Saggy Pants\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Saguenay (DDH 206)|HMCS ''Saguenay'']]'''\n*\"Sally Rand\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS St. Laurent (DDH 205)|HMCS ''St. Laurent'' (DDH 205)]]''' (decommissioned) nickname of several ships which have been named ''St. Laurent'', of which HMCS ''St. Laurent'' DDH 205 was the most recent.\n*\"San Francisco's Own\" \u2013 '''[[USS Carl Vinson (CVN-70)|USS ''Carl Vinson'']]'''\n*\"Seapuppy\" \u2013 '''[[USS Seawolf (SSN-575)|USS ''Seawolf'']]'''\n*\"Shall Not Perish\" \u2013 '''[[USS Abraham Lincoln (CVN-72)|USS ''Abraham Lincoln'']]'''\n*\"Shiny Sheff\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Sheffield|HMS ''Sheffield'']]'''\n*\"Shitty Kitty\" \u2013 '''[[USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63)|USS ''Kitty Hawk'']]'''\n*\"Showboat\" \u2013 '''[[USS North Carolina (BB-55)|USS ''North Carolina'']]'''\n*\"Sleek and Deadly Duck\" \u2013 '''[[USS Donald B. Beary (FF-1085)|USS '' Donald B. Beary'']]'''\n*\"Slack Jack\" \u2013 '''[[USS John F. Kennedy (CV-67)|USS ''John F. Kennedy'']]'''\n*\"Smiley\" \u2013 '''[[USS Jimmy Carter (SSN-23)|USS ''Jimmy Carter (SSN-23)'']]''' \u2013 nickname of former US President Carter\n*\"The Smoke\" \u2013 '''[[HMS London (69)|HMS ''London'']]'''\n*\"Sodak\" \u2013 '''{{USS|South Dakota|BB-49|6}}'''\n*\"USS Spring-a-leak\" \u2013 [[USS Springfield (CL-66)|'''USS ''Springfield (CLG-7)''''']] \u2013 for her alleged degraded engineering condition near the completion of her final deployment as Sixth Fleet Flagship (over 3 years)\n*\"Spurious\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Furious|47|6}}'''<ref>[http://www.royal-navy.org/shiplist/index.php?option=com_content&task=section&id=5&Itemid=13]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*\"Starship Vinson\" \u2013 '''[[USS Carl Vinson (CVN-70)|USS ''Carl Vinson'']]'''\n*\"Steel Cat\" \u2013 '''[[HMAS Brisbane (D-41)|HMAS ''Brisbane'']]'''\n*\"Stinkin Lincoln\" \u2013 '''[[USS Abraham Lincoln (CVN-72)|USS ''Abraham Lincoln'']]'''\n*\"Suckin' 60 From Dixie\", or \"Suckin' Sara\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Saratoga|CV60|6}}'''\n*\"Surunmaa\" \u2013 [[Finnish navy]] corvette '''[[Turunmaa class gunboat|Turunmaa]]'''. Literally \"land of sorrow\".\n*\"Swanky Franky\" \u2013 '''[[USS Franklin D. Roosevelt (CV-42)|USS Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n*\"Swayback Maru\" \u2013 '''[[USS Salt Lake City (CA-25)|USS ''Salt Lake City'']]'''\n*\"Stressex\" \u2013 '''[[USS Essex (LHD-2)|USS ''Essex'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Steamin' Deuce\" \u2013 '''[[USS Essex (LHD-2)|USS ''Essex'']]''';  humorous malapropism\n*\"Slimey Lymie\" \u2013 '''[[USS Lyman K. Swenson (DD-729)|USS ''Lyman K. Swenson'']]'''\n*\"Saint Pauline\" \u2013 '''[[USS Saint Paul (CA-73)|USS ''Saint Paul'']]'''; Humorous malapropism\n*\"The Stain\" \u2013 '''[[USS Stein (FF-1065)|USS ''Stein'']]'''\n*\"Special K\" \u2013 '''[[USNS Kawishiwi (T-AO-146)|USS ''Kawishiwi'']]'''\n*\u201cSan Jack\u201d or \u201cFlagship of the Texas Navy\u201d: '''[[USS San Jacinto (CVL-30)|USS ''San Jacinto'']]'''.\n\n==T==\n*\"T2\" \u2013 '''[[USS Tullibee (SSN-597)|USS ''Tullibee'']]''' \u2013 This nickname was used to identify the second ship named ''Tullibee'' (SSN 597) from the first '''[[USS Tullibee (SS-284)|''Tullibee'']]''' (SS 284).\n*\"T.R.\" \u2013 '''[[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'']]'''\n*\"Tea Boat\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Ceylon (C30)|HMS ''Ceylon'']]'''\n*\"[[Tea Chest]]\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Thetis|HMS ''Thetis'']]'''\n*\"Teacup\" \u2013 '''[[USS Tecumseh (SSBN-628)|USS ''Tecumseh'']]'''\n*\"Tico\" \u2013 '''[[USS Ticonderoga (CG-47)|USS ''Ticonderoga'']]'''\n*\"Tiddly Quid\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Royal Sovereign (05)|HMS ''Royal Sovereign'']]'''. Both ''quid'' and ''sovereign'' are synonymous to [[pound sterling]].\n*\"Tin Duck\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Iron Duke (1912)|HMS ''Iron Duke'']]'''\n*\"Three-Quarter Mile Island\" \u2013 '''[[USS Enterprise (CVN-65)|USS ''Enterprise'' (CVN-65)]]''' (a pun on ''Three Mile Island'')\n*\"The Toothless Terror\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Scylla (98)|HMS ''Scylla'']]'''\n*\"Toasted O\" \u2013 '''[[USS Oriskany (CV-34)|USS ''Oriskany'']]'''\n*\"Traffie\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Trafalgar (1887)|HMS ''Trafalgar'']]'''\n*\"Trawler Mauler\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Nipigon (DDH 266)|HMCS ''Nipigon'']]''' \u2013 stems from an incident in the late 1980s when ''Nipigon'' sank a civilian fishing trawler for being a hazard to shipping\n*\"Tullibeast\" \u2013 '''[[USS Tullibee (SSN-597)|USS ''Tullibee'']]'''\n*\"The Tartan Terror\" \u2013 '''[[HMAS Stuart (FFH 153)|HMAS ''Stuart'']]'''\n*\"Tottenham\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Hotspur (H01)|HMS ''Hotspur'']]'''. After [[association football|football]] team [[Tottenham Hotspur]].\n*\"Tupperware\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Wilton (M1116)|HMS ''Wilton'']]'''. First warship to be constructed from [[Glass-reinforced plastic]].\n*\"Tuska class\" \u2013 Finnish navy '''[[Tuima class missile boat]]s'''. ''Tuska'' means \"agony\" in Finnish.\n* \"Tortanic\" \u2013 '''USS ''Tortuga'' (LSD-46)'''\n* \"Top Gun\" \u2013 '''USS ''Ranger'' (CV/CVA-61)'''\n\n==U==\n*\"Uproarious\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Glorious|HMS ''Glorious'']]'''<ref>[http://www.royal-navy.org/shiplist/index.php?option=com_content&task=section&id=5&Itemid=13]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==V==\n*\"VDQ\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Ville de Qu\u00e9bec (FFH 332)|NCSM ''Ville de Qu\u00e9bec'']]'''. Note that as a designated French-language unit, she properly uses the title ''Navire canadien de Sa Majest\u00e9'' (NCSM), which is the French translation of ''Her Majesty's Canadian Ship'' (HMCS)).\n*\"Von Stupid\" \u2013 '''[[USS Von Steuben (SSBN-632)|USS ''Von Steuben'']]'''\n*\"Vince\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Invincible (R05)|HMS ''Invincible]]'''''\n*\"Vinny\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Vincennes|CA-44}}'''''\n\n==W==\n* \"Weavy\" \u2013 '''[[USS West Virginia (BB-48)|USS ''West Virginia'']]'''\n* \"Wet Ass Queen\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Wetaskiwin (K175)|HMCS ''Wetaskiwin'']]'''<ref>[http://www.battleships-cruisers.co.uk/canadian_navy.htm]</ref>\n* \"Winter Pig\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Winnipeg (FFH 338)|HMCS ''Winnipeg'']]'''\n* \"Wisky\" \u2013 '''[[USS Wisconsin (BB-64)|USS ''Wisconsin'']]'''\n* \"Wicked Witch of the West\" - '''[[USS Wichita (AOR-1)| USS ''Wichita'']]'''\n\n==X==\n{{Empty section|date=October 2010}}\n\n==Y==\n\n* \"The Y\" \u2013 '''[[USS Yakutat (AVP-32)|USCGC ''Yakutat'']]'''\n\n==Z==\n*\"Zippo\" \u2013 '''[[USS Forrestal (CVA-59)|USS ''Forrestal'']]'''<ref>[http://unitpages.military.com/unitpages/unit.do?id=200205]</ref>\n*\"Zoo (The) \u2013 '''[[USS Kalamazoo (AOR-6)|USS ''Kalamazoo'']]'''\n\n==Abbreviations==\n*'''NCSM''' \u2013 \"Navire canadien de Sa Majest\u00e9\"; applied to [[Royal Canadian Navy]] and [[Canadian Forces]] vessels designated as French-language units.\n*'''HMAS''' \u2013 \"His/Her Majesty's Australian Ship\"; applied to [[Royal Australian Navy]] vessels\n*'''HMCS''' \u2013 \"His/Her Majesty's Canadian Ship\"; applied to [[Royal Canadian Navy]] and [[Canadian Forces]] vessels\n*'''HMNZS''' \u2013 \"His/Her Majesty's New Zealand Ship\"; applied to [[Royal New Zealand Navy]] vessels\n*'''HMS''' \u2013 \"His/Her Majesty's Ship\"; applied to [[Royal Navy]] vessels\n*'''USS''' \u2013 \"United States Ship\"; applied to [[United States Navy]] vessels\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Lists}}\n* [[List of nicknames of British Army regiments]]\n* [[Lists of nicknames]] \u2013 nickname list articles on Wikipedia\n* [[Nicknames of U.S. Army divisions]]\n* [[Regimental nicknames of the Canadian Forces]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of nicknames|Warships]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe following is a list of [[warship]]s listed by [[nickname]]. See below for a key to abbreviations.\n\n{{compact ToC|side=yes|top=yes|num=yes}}\n\n==A==\n* \"Abe\" \u2013 '''[[USS Abraham Lincoln (CVN-72)|USS ''Abraham Lincoln'']]''''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20051218093115/http://www.news.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=13848]</ref> [[Abraham Lincoln]] is often informally referred to as \"Abe\" or \"Stink'n Lincoln\"\n*\"Ageless Warrior\" \u2013 '''[[USS Coral Sea (CV-43)|USS ''Coral Sea'']]'''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20041228072024/http://www.cnsl.spear.navy.mil/jamesewilliams/WILLIAMS/cmc.htm]</ref><ref>[http://www.usscoralsea.net/]</ref>\n*\"Aggie\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Agamemnon (1906)|HMS ''Agamemnon'']]'''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235019/http://royalnavy.mod.uk/server/show/conWebDoc.1268/changeNav/3533]</ref>\n*\"Aggie on Horseback\" \u2013 '''[[Shoreham-class sloop|HMS ''Weston'']]''';<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235019/http://royalnavy.mod.uk/server/show/conWebDoc.1268/changeNav/3533]</ref> nickname named for [[Agnes Weston]], a [[Temperance movement|temperance]] and [[sailor]]'s advocate; \"on horseback\" is a jocular mistranslation of [[Latin language|Latin]] ''\"super-mare\"'' (\"on the sea\"), ''\"mare\"'' being equated with a female horse\n*\"'A Gin Court\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Agincourt|HMS ''Agincourt'']]'''; Battleship seized from Turkey in 1914; because of its luxurious Turkish outfit\n*\"Algonquatraz\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Algonquin (DDG 283)|HMCS ''Algonquin'' (DDG 283)]]'''\n*\"'Am and Tripe\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Amphitrite (1898)|HMS ''Amphitrite'']]''';<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235019/http://royalnavy.mod.uk/server/show/conWebDoc.1268/changeNav/3533]</ref> humorous malapropism\n*\"America's Favorite Carrier\" \u2013 '''[[USS Carl Vinson (CVN-70)|USS ''Carl Vinson'']]'''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060906043244/http://www.cvn70.navy.mil/presrel/18NOV04_Vinson%20Birthday.html]</ref>\n*\"Angry Cat\" \u2013 '''[[French battleship Henri IV|French ship ''Henri IV'']]''';<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060509160813/http://www.royal-navy.mod.uk/server/show/nav.3818]</ref> named so by the British, a play on the pronunciation of \"Henri Quatre\"\n*\"Archdeacon\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Venerable (1899)|HMS ''Venerable'']]''';<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235019/http://royalnavy.mod.uk/server/show/conWebDoc.1268/changeNav/3533]</ref> a play on the phrase \"venerable archdeacon\"\n*\"Athabee\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Athabaskan (DDG 282)|HMCS ''Athabaskan'' (DDG 282)]]'''\n\n==B==\n*\"Babe Lincoln\" \u2013 '''[[USS Abraham Lincoln (CVN-72)|USS ''Abraham Lincoln'']]'''; reference to her 1995 deployment, the first United States warship to put to sea with women in combat roles\n*\"Battle Cat\" \u2013 '''[[USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63)|USS ''Kitty Hawk'']]'''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20051129002924/http://www.news.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=12115]</ref>\n*\"Battle Schmoozer\", \"Belcrash\" \u2013 '''[[USS Belknap (CG-26)|USS ''Belknap'']]'''; reference her collision with the USS ''Kennedy'' in 1975\n*\"Battle Star\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Carl Vinson|CVN-70}}\n*\"Big Ben\" \u2013 '''[[USS Franklin (CV-13)|USS ''Franklin'']]''';<ref>[http://www.ussfranklin.org]</ref> the ship is named after [[Benjamin Franklin]]\n*\"Big D\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Dallas|SSN-700|6}}'''; given to the boat to denote being named in honor of the [[Dallas, Texas|city of Dallas]].\n*\"The Big E\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}''' (CV-6)<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060427021258/http://www.chinfo.navy.mil/navpalib/ships/carriers/histories/cv06-enterprise/cv06-enterprise.html]</ref> and '''[[USS Enterprise (CVN-65)|USS ''Enterprise'']]''' (CVN-65)<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060427092124/http://www.chinfo.navy.mil/navpalib/ships/carriers/histories/cv65-enterprise/cv65-enterprise.html]</ref>\n*\"The Big J\" \u2013 '''[[USS New Jersey (BB-62)|USS ''New Jersey'']]'''<ref>[http://www.ussnewjersey.com/]</ref>\n*\"Big John\" \u2013 '''[[USS John F. Kennedy (CV-67)|USS ''John F. Kennedy'']]'''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060624094755/http://www.nol.navy.mil/homepages/cv67/]</ref>\n*\"Big Lizzie\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Queen Elizabeth|1913|6}}'''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235019/http://royalnavy.mod.uk/server/show/conWebDoc.1268/changeNav/3533]</ref>\n*\"Big Mamie\" \u2013  '''[[USS Massachusetts (BB-59)|USS ''Massachusetts'']]'''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061207083427/http://www.chinfo.navy.mil/navpalib/ships/battleships/massachusetts/bb59-mass.html]</ref>\n*\"The Big Nasty\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Nassau|LHA-4|6}}'''\n*\"The Big Stick\" \u2013 '''[[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'']]''';<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060616054333/http://www.tr.surfor.navy.mil/default.aspx]</ref> based on [[Theodore Roosevelt]]'s quotation, \"Speak softly and carry a big stick\".<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/treasures/trm139.html]</ref> Also used for the {{USS|Iowa|BB-61|6}} for its role as the '''Big Stick of the Pacific''' during most of the naval battles it participated in.\n*\"Big Gray Deuce\" \u2013 '''[[USS Essex (LHD-2)|USS ''Essex'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Billy Ruffian\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Bellerophon (1907)|HMS ''Bellerophon'']]''';<ref>[http://royalnavy.mod.uk]</ref> humorous mispronunciation\n*\"The Black Dragon\" \u2013 '''{{USS|New Jersey|BB-62|6}}'''\n*\"The Blue Ghost\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Lexington|CV-16}}'''; nickname supposedly bestowed by Japanese radio propagandist [[Tokyo Rose]] because of the color of her camouflage painting and because she repeatedly disproved reports that she had been sunk<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060426190524/http://militaryhistory.about.com/od/navalwarfare/a/blueghost.htm]</ref>\n*\"Bonnie\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Bonaventure (CVL 22)|HMCS ''Bonaventure'']]'''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060510134926/http://www.airforce.forces.gc.ca/equip/historical/bonaventurelst_e.asp]</ref>\n*\"Bonnie Dick\" \u2013 '''[[USS Bon Homme Richard (CV-31)|USS ''Bom Homme Richard'' CV/CVA-31]]''' and '''[[USS Bonhomme Richard (LHD-6)|USS ''Bomhomme Richard'' (LHD-6)]]'''\n*\"Buckin' Bronco\" \u2013 '''[[USS Colorado (BB-45)|USS ''Colorado (BB-45)'']]'''\n*\"Building (hull number)\" \u2013 a U.S. Navy joke about ships that don't go to sea much.\n**\"Building 575\" \u2013 '''[[USS Seawolf (SSN-575)|USS ''Seawolf'' (SSN-575)]]'''\n**\"Building 597\" \u2013  '''[[USS Tullibee (SSN-597)|USS ''Tullibee'' (SSN-597)]]'''\n**\"Building 21\" \u2013 '''[[USS Seawolf (SSN-21)|USS ''Seawolf'' (SSN-21)]]'''\n**\"Building 11\" \u2013 '''[[USS Coronado (AGF-11)|USS ''Coronado'' (AGF-11)]]'''\n*\"Bulldog of the Navy\" \u2013 '''[[USS Oregon (BB-3)|USS ''Oregon'' (BB-3)]]'''\n*\"The Big Risk\" \u2013 '''[[USS Oriskany (CV-34)|USS ''Oriskany (CV-34)]]'''\n*\"Bag Lady\" \u2013 '''[[USS Bagley (FF-1069)|USS ''Bagley (FF-1069)'']]'''; humorous malaproprism\n*\"Berzerkly\" \u2013 '''[[USS Berkeley (DDG-15)|USS ''Berkeley (DDG-15)'']]'''; humorous malaproprism\n*\"Broke\" \u2013 '''[[USS Brooke (FFG-1)|USS ''Brooke (FFG-1)'']]'''; humorous malaproprism\n\n==C==\n*\"C-ville\" \u2013 '''[[USS Chancellorsville (CG-62)|USS ''Chancellorsville'']]'''\n*\"Cannabis\" \u2013 '''[[USS Canopus (AS-34)|USS ''Canopus'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Can o\u2019 Pus\" \u2013 '''USS ''Canopus''''' (1980s reference to first 20% female crew.)\n*\"Can Opener\" \u2013 '''[[USS John F. Kennedy (CV-67)|USS ''John F. Kennedy'']]''', after collision with USS ''Belknap''\n*\"Century One\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Centurion (1911)|HMS ''Centurion'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Cheer Up Ship\" \u2013 '''[[USS Nevada (BB-36)|USS ''Nevada (BB-36)'']]'''\n*\u201dChesapeake Raider\u201d - '''[[USS Wyoming (BB-32)|USS ''Wyoming (BB-32)'']]''', nickname given after frequent sightings of the ship in the Chesapeake Bay during World War Two.\n*\"Christmas Anthem\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Chrysanthemum (1917)|HMS ''Chrysanthemum'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Chuckie V\" \u2013 '''[[USS Carl Vinson (CVN-70)|USS ''Carl Vinson'']]'''\n*\"Cocoa Boat\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Curacoa (D41)|HMS ''Curacoa'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Connie\" \u2013 '''[[USS Constellation (CV-64)|USS ''Constellation'']]'''; diminutive of ship's name\n*\"The Count\" \u2013 '''[[USS Comte de Grasse (DD-974)|USS ''Comte de Grasse'']]'''; named for [[Fran\u00e7ois Joseph Paul, marquis de Grasetilly, comte de Grasse|Comte de Grasse]] ([[French language|French]], \"Count de Grasse\"), an ally of the Americans in the [[American War of Independence]]\n*\"Curious\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Furious|47|6}}'''<ref>[http://www.royal-navy.org/shiplist/index.php?option=com_content&task=section&id=5&Itemid=13]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*\"Cellblock 70\" \u2013 '''[[USS Carl Vinson (CVN-70)|USS ''Carl Vinson'']]'''; humorous reference to restricted liberty for crew after incidents in Bremerton, WA, in the mid-1980s.\n\n==D==\n*\"Despair Ship Remorse\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Resource (F79)|HMS ''Resource'']]''';<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060509160813/http://www.royal-navy.mod.uk/server/show/nav.3818]</ref> humorous malapropism on \"Repair ship ''Resource''\"\n*\"Decrepit\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Intrepid|CV-11|6}}'''\n*\"Dirty Cush\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Cushing|DD-985|6}}'''\n*\"Dirty Two-Thirty\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Margaree (DDE 230)|HMCS ''Margaree'' (DDE 230)]]''' (decommissioned); from her hull number.\n*\"Dirty V\" \u2013 '''[[USS Carl Vinson (CVN-70)|USS ''Carl Vinson'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Dreado\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Dreadnought (1906)|HMS ''Dreadnought'']]''';<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060509160813/http://www.royal-navy.mod.uk/server/show/nav.3818]</ref> diminutive of ship's name\n*\"Dull Ass\" \u2013 '''[[USS Dallas (SSN-700)|USS ''Dallas'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Dickover\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Hyman G. Rickover|SSN-709|6}}'''\n*\"Dickey B\" \u2013 '''USS ''Richard B. Russell'' (SSN-687)'''\n*\"Dry I\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Intrepid|CV-11|6}}'''\n*\"Dippity Do\" - \u2018\u2019\u2019 USS DuPont (DD-941)\u2019\u2019\u2019\n\n==E==\n*\"Eggshells\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Achilles (1905)|HMS ''Achilles'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Enterprison\" \u2013 '''[[USS Enterprise (CVN-65)|USS ''Enterprise'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Evil I\" \u2013 {{USS|Intrepid|CV-11|6}}\n*\"Exploder\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Explorer|submarine|6}}'''; experimental & temperamental submarine fitted with dangerous [[hydrogen peroxide]] propulsion system.\n\n==F==\n*\"The Fightingest Ship in the RCN\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Haida (G63)|HMCS ''Haida'']]'''; gained this moniker by reason of sinking 14 enemy ships during patrols in the [[English Channel]] and the [[Bay of Biscay]]; she also sank more enemy surface tonnage than any other Canadian ship<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110609164429/http://www.forces.gc.ca/site/community/mapleleaf/vol_5/vol5_04/vol5-04navy.pdf]</ref>\n*\"The Fighting G\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Gloucester (D96)|HMS ''Gloucester'']]'''\n*\"The Fighting J\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Jamaica (44)|HMS ''Jamaica'']]'''\n*\"The Fighting I\" \u2013 '''[[USS Intrepid (CV-11)|USS ''Intrepid'']]'''\n*\"The Fighting Lady\" \u2013 '''[[USS Yorktown (CV-10)|USS ''Yorktown'']]'''\n*\"The Fighting Sausage\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Cumberland (F85)|HMS ''Cumberland'']]'''; from [[Cumberland sausage]]\n*\"Fighting Mary\" \u2013 '''[[USS Maryland (BB-46)|USS ''Maryland (BB-46)'']]'''\n*\"Firestal\" \u2013 '''[[USS Forrestal (CVA-59)|USS ''Forrestal'']]'''\n*\"The Five Mile Sniper\" \u2013 '''[[HMAS Brisbane (D-41)|HMAS ''Brisbane'']]'''\n*\"Flatiron\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Argus|I49|6}}'''; from the shape of the ship\n*\"Forrest Fire\" \"FID (First in Defense)\" \u2013 '''[[USS Forrestal (CVA-59)|USS ''Forrestal'']]'''; humorous malapropism, also because of the fire on deck.\n*\"Foo-De-Roo\" \u2013 '''[[USS Franklin D. Roosevelt (CV-42)|USS Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n*\"Fraser Blade\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Fraser (DDH 233)|HMCS ''Fraser'']]'''\n*\"Freddy\" \u2013 ''' [[HMCS Fredericton (FFH 337)|HMCS ''Fredericton'']]'''\n*\"Fleet Starship\" \u2013 '''USS ''Enterprise'' (CVN-65)'''\n*\"The Furry Wet Mound\" \u2013 '''USS ''Harry W. Hill'' (DD-986)''', humorous malapropism\n\n==G==\n*\"Galloping Ghost of the Java Coast\" \u2013 '''[[USS Houston (CA-30)|USS ''Houston'']]'''\n* \"George's Legs\" or \"Gorgeous Legs\" \u2013 French light cruiser '''Georges Leygues ''' \n*\"Germanclown\" \u2013 USS ''Germantown'' (LSD-42)\n*\"Ghetto\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Gato}}'''\n*\"Gipper\" \u2013 '''[[USS Ronald Reagan (CVN-76)|USS ''Ronald Reagan'']]'''; named for [[Ronald Reagan]]'s nickname, from his role of [[George Gipp|George \"The Gipper\" Gipp]] in the film [[Knute Rockne, All American]].\n*\"Gin Palace\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Agincourt (1913)|HMS ''Agincourt'']]'''; originally built for Brazilian Navy and given higher standards of comfort for officers, and lesser standards of comfort for the crew than most RN ships. Also a deliberate misspelling of the name: ''A Gin Court''.\n*\"The Gold Eagle\" \u2013 '''[[USS Carl Vinson (CVN-70)|USS ''Carl Vinson'']]'''\n*\"The Golden Devil\" ([[Dutch language|Dutch]] ''\"Den Gulden Duvel\"'') \u2013 '''[[HMS Sovereign of the Seas|HMS ''Sovereign of the Seas'']]'''\n*\"The Golden Guad\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Guadalcanal|LPH-7}}'''\n*''\"Le Grand Hotel\"'' \u2013 '''[[French ironclad Hoche|French Ironclad ''Hoche'']]'''\n*\"The Grand Old Lady\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Warspite (03)|HMS ''Warspite'']]'''<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/ww2peopleswar/stories/99/a4464399.shtml]</ref>\n*\u201dThe Galloping Ghost\u201d \u2013 '''[[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|USS ''Enterprise'' (CV-6)]]'''\n*\"The Gray Ghost\" \u2013 '''[[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|USS ''Enterprise'' (CV-6)]]'''\n*\"The Gray Lady\" \u2013 '''[[USS Lexington (CV-2)|USS ''Lexington'']]'''\n*\"The Gray Ghost\" - '''[[USS Iowa (BB-61)|USS ''Iowa'' (BB-61)]]'''\n*\"Grey Ghost\" \u2013 '''[[USS Pensacola (CA-24)|USS ''Pensacola'']]'''; nickname given by [[Tokyo Rose]]\n*\"Greenpig\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Greenling}}'''\n*\"GW\" \u2013 '''[[USS George Washington (CVN-73)|USS ''George Washington'']]'''; initials of the ship's namesake\n\n==H==\n*\"The Ham\" \u2013 {{USS|Ingraham|FFG-61|6}}\n*\"Happy Valley\" \u2013 '''[[USS Valley Forge (CVA-45)|USS ''Valley Forge'']]'''\n*\"He-Cat\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Hecate|HMS ''Hecate'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"HMAS Can Opener\" \u2013 '''{{HMAS|Melbourne|R21|6}}'''; given by US Navy sailors for the ship's part in the sinking of the US Navy destroyer {{USS|Frank E. Evans||6}}. ''Melbourne'' previously sank another destroyer, {{HMAS|Voyager|D04|6}}, in a similar collision.\n*\"HMS Me\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Queen Elizabeth|R08|6}}'''; from a cake presented to [[Elizabeth II]] during her first visit to the ship.<ref>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5155401/Lizzie-meet-Big-Lizzie-Majesty-steps-aboard-ship.html</ref>\n*\"HMS Refit\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Renown|1916|6}}''';\n*\"HMS Repair\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Repulse (1916)|HMS ''Repulse'']]'''\n*\"Hiroshima\" \u2013 '''[[Soviet submarine K-19|Soviet submarine ''K-19'']]''', due to a nuclear accident onboard\n*\"Hockey Puck \u2013 '''{{USS|Haleakala|AE-25}}'''; humorous malapropism \n*\"Holiday Express\" \u2013 '''[[USS Bunker Hill (CV-17)|USS ''Bunker Hill'']]'''\n*\"Holiday Inn\" \u2013 '''[[USS Bunker Hill (CV-17)|USS ''Bunker Hill'']]'''\n*\"HST\" \u2013 '''[[USS Harry S. Truman (CVN-75)|USS ''Harry S. Truman'']]'''; initials of the ship's namesake [[Harry S. Truman]]\n*\"Hairy Ass\" \u2013 '''[[USS Harry S. Truman (CVN-75)|USS ''Harry S. Truman'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Hymi G\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Hyman G. Rickover|SSN-709|6}}'''\n*\"Happy Harry\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Harry W. Hill|DD-986}}'''\n*\"Hotel Yamato\" \u2013 '''[[Japanese battleship Yamato|Japanese battleship ''Yamato'']]'''; due to the amount of time spent at Truk between August 1942 and May 1943\n\n==I==\n*\"Ike\" \u2013 '''[[USS Dwight D. Eisenhower (CVN-69)|USS ''Dwight D. Eisenhower'']]'''; based on nickname of namesake, [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]]\n*\"Ikeatraz\" \u2013 '''[[USS Dwight D. Eisenhower (CVN-69)|USS ''Dwight D. Eisenhower'']]'''; derogatory nickname given to those that served on board and had gotten in trouble in some way.\n*\"Indy\" \u2013 '''[[USS Independence (CV-62)|USS ''Independence'']]'''\n*\"Iron Duck\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Iron Duke|HMS ''Iron Duke'']]'''\n*\"Fighting I\" \u2013 '''[[USS Intrepid (CV-11)|USS ''Intrepid'']]'''\n*\"Ichiban Benjo Maru\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Ajax|AR-6}}'''; due to an outbreak of bacillary dysentery that required quarantine\n*\"Iron Woman\" {{USS|Cabot|CV-16|6}}\n\n==J==\n*\"Jimmy K\" \u2013 '''[[USS James K. Polk (SSBN-645)|USS ''James K. Polk'']]'''\n*\"Johnny Reb\" \u2013 '''[[USS John C. Stennis (CVN-74)|USS ''John C. Stennis'']]'''\n\n==K==\n*\"Kaarnavene\" \u2013 [[Finnish Navy]] '''[[Nuoli class fast gunboat]]s'''. The name means literally \"bark boat\": they were made from non-magnetic mahogany.\n*\"Kami-ha-ha\" \u2013 '''[[USS Kamehameha (SSBN-642)|USS ''Kamehameha'']]''';  humorous malapropism\n*\"King of Tomahawks\" \u2013 '''[[USS John Young (DD-973)|USS ''John Young'']]'''; probably after the ship's [[BGM-109 Tomahawk]] weapons system, or  \"The John Bone\" humorous malapropisms\n*\"Shitty Kitty\" \u2013 '''[[USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63)|USS ''Kitty Hawk'']]''';  humorous malapropism<ref name=\"seattlest\">{{cite web\n  | last = Prohaska\n  | first = Kim\n  | title = The USS Shitty Kitty Decommissioned\n  | work = Seattlest Daily\n  | date = 2009-05-14\n  | url = http://seattlest.com/2009/05/14/the_uss_shitty_kitty_decommissioned.php\n  | accessdate = 2010-10-16\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111001135314/http://seattlest.com/2009/05/14/the_uss_shitty_kitty_decommissioned.php\n  | archive-date = 2011-10-01\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref>\n*\"Knockwood\" \u2013 '''[[USS Lockwood (FF-1064)|USS ''Lockwood'']]'''\n\n==L==\n*\"Lady Lex\" \u2013 '''[[USS Lexington (CV-2)|USS ''Lexington'']]'''\n*\"Lady Lou\" \u2013 '''[[USS Louisville (CA-28)|USS ''Louisville'']]'''\n*\"Long Delayed\" \u2013 '''[[HMAS Adelaide (1918)|HMAS ''Adelaide'']]'''; rhyming play on ship's name. Fitting out and completion of the ship were delayed (almost 3 years) due to the loss of important machinery parts, as a result of enemy action, which gave rise to the nickname.\n*\"The Lord's Own\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Vengeance (1899)|HMS ''Vengeance'']]'''; derived from the phrase \"The Lord's own vengeance\", based on the sentiment of [[Epistle to the Romans|Romans]]<ref>[http://www.zianet.com/maxey/Roman24.htm 12:19]</ref>\n*\"Lost and Confused\" \u2013 '''[[USS Lewis and Clark (SSBN-644)|USS ''Lewis and Clark'']]'''\n*\"Lucky A\"  \u2013 '''[[USS Alabama (BB-60)|USS ''Alabama]]'''\n*\"Lucky E\"  \u2013 '''[[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|USS ''Enterprise]]'''\n*\"Lucky 26\" \u2013 '''[[HNoMS Stord (G26)|HNoMS ''Stord'']]'''\n*\"Lusty\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Illustrious (R06)|HMS ''Illustrious]]'''''\n*\"Lucky Number 7\" \u2013 '''[[USNS Rainier (T-AOE-7)|USS ''Rainier'']]''' \u2013 The hull number.\n\n==M==\n*\"Maggie\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Magnificent (1894)|HMS ''Magnificent'']]'''; '''[[HMCS Magnificent (CVL 21)|HMCS ''Magnificent'']]'''\n*\"The Mighty Hood\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Hood|51|6}}'''\n*\"Mighty O\" \u2013 '''[[USS Oriskany (CV-34)|USS ''Oriskany'']]'''\n*\"Mighty T\" \u2013 '''[[USS Texas (BB-35)|USS ''Texas (BB-35)'']]'''\n*\"Mighty Y\" \u2013 '''[[USS Yakutat (AVP-32)|USCGC ''Yakutat'']]'''\n*\"Mighty Mo\" \u2013 '''[[USS Missouri (BB-63)|USS ''Missouri'']]'''\n*\"Mighty Moo\" \u2013 '''[[USS Cowpens (CVL-25)|USS ''Cowpens'']]'''\n*\"Mobile Chernobyl\" \u2013 '''[[USS Enterprise (CVN-65)|USS ''Enterprise]]'''\n*\"Moskvitch\" \u2013 [[Finnish navy]] '''[[Tuima class missile boat]]s'''. Soviet-built [[Moskvitch]] cars had notoriously poor reputation in Finland.\n* \"Motel 6\" \u2013 '''USS ''Bonhomme Richard'' (LHD-6)'''\n* \"Midway Magic\" \u2013 '''USS ''Midway'' (CV-41)'''\n\n==N==\n*\"Nasty Asty\" \u2013 '''[[USS Astoria (CA-34)|USS ''Astoria'']]''' \n*\"Nasty Nick\" \u2013 '''[[USS Nicholas (FFG-47)|USS ''Nicholas'']]''', name given by crew due to the proclivity of the ship's AC units to break down in hot weather.\n*\"Nelly\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Nelson|28|6}}''' \u2013 also \"Nelsol\" \u2013 from fleet oilers with names ending in 'ol' that the Nelson class looked similar to in silhouette. \n*\"Niffy Jane\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Iphigenia|HMS ''Iphigenia'']]'''\n*\"NO Boat\" \u2013 '''[[USS New Orleans (CA-32)|USS ''New Orleans'']]'''\n*\"Northo\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Northumberland (1865)|HMS ''Northumberland'']]'''\n\n==O==\n*\"O'Broken\" \u2013 '''[[USS O'Brien (DD-975)|USS ''O'Brien'']]'''\n*\"The O-Boat\" \u2013 '''[[USS Oriskany (CV-34)|USS ''Oriskany'']]'''\n*\"Old Bones\" \u2013 '''[[HIJMS Kongo|Japanese battleship ''Kong\u014d'']]'''\n*\"Old Falling Apart\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Pennsylvania|BB-38}}''', from firing so many rounds during the bombardment of Guam, she appeared to be falling apart.\n*\"Old Formy\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Formidable (67)|HMS ''Formidable'']]'''\n*\"Old Hoodoo\" \u2013 '''[[USS Texas (1892)|USS ''Texas (1892)'']]'''\n*\"Old Mary\" \u2013 '''[[USS Maryland (BB-46)|USS ''Maryland (BB-46)'']]'''\n*\"The Old Grey Ghost of the Borneo Coast\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Albion (R07)|HMS ''Albion'']]'''<ref>http://www.hmsalbion.org.uk/{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*\"Old Ironsides\" \u2013 '''[[USS Constitution|USS ''Constitution'']]'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussconstitution.navy.mil/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070213180914/http://www.ussconstitution.navy.mil/ |archivedate=2007-02-13 }}</ref>\n*\"The Old Lady\" \u2013  '''[[HMS Warspite (03)|HMS ''Warspite'']]''', from a comment by [[Andrew Cunningham, 1st Viscount Cunningham of Hyndhope|Viscount Cunningham]];<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.postalheritage.org.uk/exhibitions/ww2stamps/cunningham |title=The British Postal Museum & Archive - Viscount Cunningham & HMS Warspite<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2006-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060822083953/http://www.postalheritage.org.uk/exhibitions/ww2stamps/cunningham |archive-date=2006-08-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> impressed by the vintage ship's speed during a mission to aid the British Army in Sicily, Cunningham remarked, \"When the old lady lifts her skirts she can run.\"<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/ww2peopleswar/stories/08/a4134908.shtml BBC - WW2 People's War - My Life My War - Chapter 12c<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*\"Old Lady of the Sea\" \u2013 '''[[USS New York (BB-34)|USS ''New York (BB-34)'']]'''\n*\"Old Salt\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Nimitz|CVN-68|6}}'''\n*\"One-Eye\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Polyphemus (1881)|HMS ''Polyphemus'']]'''; [[Polyphemus]] was a [[cyclops]] in [[Greek mythology]]\n*\"Orjalaiva Kurjala\" \u2013 [[Finnish Navy]] corvette '''[[Turunmaa class gunboat|Karjala]]'''. The word ''orjalaiva'' means [[slave ship]] in Finnish, while ''Kurjala'' references the Finnish word ''kurja'' (\"miserable\").\n*\"Outrageous\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Courageous (50)|HMS ''Courageous'']]''';<ref>[http://www.royal-navy.org/shiplist/index.php?option=com_content&task=section&id=5&Itemid=13]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }},</ref> humorous [[malapropism]]\n*\"The Oki Boat\" \u2013 '''[[USS Okinawa (LPH-3)|USS ''Okinawa'']]'''\n\n==P==\n*\"Pepper Pot\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Penelope|97|6}}''' \u2013 while docked in Valletta harbour, during the [[Siege of Malta (World War II)|Siege of Malta]], she was bombed so much she resembled a pepper pot\n*\"Pierwolf\" \u2013 '''[[USS Seawolf (SSN-575)|USS ''Seawolf'']]'''\n*\"The Pool\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Liverpool (C11)|HMS ''Liverpool'']]'''\n*\"Proud Pete\" \u2013 '''[[USS Peterson (DD-969)|USS ''Peterson'']]''';  play on \"Pete\" as a diminutive of \"Peterson\", and on the ship's [[motto]], \"Proud Tradition\"\n*\"Prune Barge\" \u2013 '''[[USS California (BB-44)|USS ''California'']]<ref>http://ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/ships/logs/BB/bb44-schaffran.html</ref>\n*\"Puffington\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Effingham (D98)|HMS ''Effingham'']]'''\n*\"Puuhamaa\" \u2013 Finnish navy [[minelayer]] '''[[Finnish minelayer Pohjanmaa|Pohjanmaa]]'''. An ironical remark of [[Puuhamaa]] amusement park.\n*\"Sweet Pea\" \u2013 '''[[USS Portland (CA-33)|USS ''Portland'']]'''\n*\"Pig Boat\" - '''[[USS California (CGN-36)|USS ''California'']]'''; The resemblance of the bear on the ship's badge to that of a pig.\n\n==Q==\n \n*\"Queerfish\" \u2013 '''[[USS Queenfish (SS-393)|USS ''Queenfish'']]'''\n*\"Quiet Warrior\" \u2013 '''[[USS Spruance (DD-963)|USS ''Spruance'']]'''\n\n==R==\n*\"The Red-Eye\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Huron (DDG 281)|HMCS ''Huron'' (DDG 281)]]''' (decommissioned); so named for the tobacco flower blossom on the ship's badge.\n*\"Refit\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Renown|1916|6}}'''\n*\"Repair\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Repulse (1916)|HMS ''Repulse'']]'''\n*\"Rezzo\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Resolution (09)|HMS ''Resolution'']]'''\n*\"Rosie\" \u2013 '''[[USS Franklin D. Roosevelt (CV-42)|USS Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n*\"Rough Rider\" \u2013 '''[[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'']]'''\n*\"Rodnol\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Rodney (29)|HMS ''Rodney'']]''' \u2013 from fleet oilers with names ending in 'ol'\n*\"Ruosteensilm\u00e4\" \u2013 [[Finnish Navy]] '''[[Finnish minelayer Ruotsinsalmi|minelayer Ruotsinsalmi]]'''. The name means ''Rusty Eye'' in Finnish.\n*\"Rusty-guts\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Restigouche (DDE 257)|HMCS ''Restigouche'']]'''<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/ArticleNews/TPStory/LAC/20051105/OBPIERS05/TPObituaries/?pageRequested=all]</ref>\n*\"Rusty W\" \u2013 '''[[USS Washington (BB-56)|USS ''Washington'']]'''\n\n==S==\n*\"Sara\", \"Super Sara\", \"Sorry Sara\", \"Sister Sara\", \"Stripe-Stack Sara\", \"Sinking Sara\" or \"Sara Maru\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Saratoga|CV-3|6}}'''\n*\"Saggy Pants\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Saguenay (DDH 206)|HMCS ''Saguenay'']]'''\n*\"Sally Rand\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS St. Laurent (DDH 205)|HMCS ''St. Laurent'' (DDH 205)]]''' (decommissioned) nickname of several ships which have been named ''St. Laurent'', of which HMCS ''St. Laurent'' DDH 205 was the most recent.\n*\"San Francisco's Own\" \u2013 '''[[USS Carl Vinson (CVN-70)|USS ''Carl Vinson'']]'''\n*\"Seapuppy\" \u2013 '''[[USS Seawolf (SSN-575)|USS ''Seawolf'']]'''\n*\"Shall Not Perish\" \u2013 '''[[USS Abraham Lincoln (CVN-72)|USS ''Abraham Lincoln'']]'''\n*\"Shiny Sheff\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Sheffield|HMS ''Sheffield'']]'''\n*\"Shitty Kitty\" \u2013 '''[[USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63)|USS ''Kitty Hawk'']]'''\n*\"Showboat\" \u2013 '''[[USS North Carolina (BB-55)|USS ''North Carolina'']]'''\n*\"Sleek and Deadly Duck\" \u2013 '''[[USS Donald B. Beary (FF-1085)|USS '' Donald B. Beary'']]'''\n*\"Slack Jack\" \u2013 '''[[USS John F. Kennedy (CV-67)|USS ''John F. Kennedy'']]'''\n*\"Smiley\" \u2013 '''[[USS Jimmy Carter (SSN-23)|USS ''Jimmy Carter (SSN-23)'']]''' \u2013 nickname of former US President Carter\n*\"The Smoke\" \u2013 '''[[HMS London (69)|HMS ''London'']]'''\n*\"Sodak\" \u2013 '''{{USS|South Dakota|BB-49|6}}'''\n*\"USS Spring-a-leak\" \u2013 [[USS Springfield (CL-66)|'''USS ''Springfield (CLG-7)''''']] \u2013 for her alleged degraded engineering condition near the completion of her final deployment as Sixth Fleet Flagship (over 3 years)\n*\"Spurious\" \u2013 '''{{HMS|Furious|47|6}}'''<ref>[http://www.royal-navy.org/shiplist/index.php?option=com_content&task=section&id=5&Itemid=13]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*\"Starship Vinson\" \u2013 '''[[USS Carl Vinson (CVN-70)|USS ''Carl Vinson'']]'''\n*\"Steel Cat\" \u2013 '''[[HMAS Brisbane (D-41)|HMAS ''Brisbane'']]'''\n*\"Stinkin Lincoln\" \u2013 '''[[USS Abraham Lincoln (CVN-72)|USS ''Abraham Lincoln'']]'''\n*\"Suckin' 60 From Dixie\", or \"Suckin' Sara\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Saratoga|CV60|6}}'''\n*\"Surunmaa\" \u2013 [[Finnish navy]] corvette '''[[Turunmaa class gunboat|Turunmaa]]'''. Literally \"land of sorrow\".\n*\"Swanky Franky\" \u2013 '''[[USS Franklin D. Roosevelt (CV-42)|USS Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n*\"Swayback Maru\" \u2013 '''[[USS Salt Lake City (CA-25)|USS ''Salt Lake City'']]'''\n*\"Stressex\" \u2013 '''[[USS Essex (LHD-2)|USS ''Essex'']]'''; humorous malapropism\n*\"Steamin' Deuce\" \u2013 '''[[USS Essex (LHD-2)|USS ''Essex'']]''';  humorous malapropism\n*\"Slimey Lymie\" \u2013 '''[[USS Lyman K. Swenson (DD-729)|USS ''Lyman K. Swenson'']]'''\n*\"Saint Pauline\" \u2013 '''[[USS Saint Paul (CA-73)|USS ''Saint Paul'']]'''; Humorous malapropism\n*\"The Stain\" \u2013 '''[[USS Stein (FF-1065)|USS ''Stein'']]'''\n*\"Special K\" \u2013 '''[[USNS Kawishiwi (T-AO-146)|USS ''Kawishiwi'']]'''\n*\u201cSan Jack\u201d or \u201cFlagship of the Texas Navy\u201d: '''[[USS San Jacinto (CVL-30)|USS ''San Jacinto'']]'''.\n\n==T==\n*\"T2\" \u2013 '''[[USS Tullibee (SSN-597)|USS ''Tullibee'']]''' \u2013 This nickname was used to identify the second ship named ''Tullibee'' (SSN 597) from the first '''[[USS Tullibee (SS-284)|''Tullibee'']]''' (SS 284).\n*\"T.R.\" \u2013 '''[[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'']]'''\n*\"Tea Boat\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Ceylon (C30)|HMS ''Ceylon'']]'''\n*\"[[Tea Chest]]\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Thetis|HMS ''Thetis'']]'''\n*\"Teacup\" \u2013 '''[[USS Tecumseh (SSBN-628)|USS ''Tecumseh'']]'''\n*\"Tico\" \u2013 '''[[USS Ticonderoga (CG-47)|USS ''Ticonderoga'']]'''\n*\"Tiddly Quid\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Royal Sovereign (05)|HMS ''Royal Sovereign'']]'''. Both ''quid'' and ''sovereign'' are synonymous to [[pound sterling]].\n*\"Tin Duck\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Iron Duke (1912)|HMS ''Iron Duke'']]'''\n*\"Three-Quarter Mile Island\" \u2013 '''[[USS Enterprise (CVN-65)|USS ''Enterprise'' (CVN-65)]]''' (a pun on ''Three Mile Island'')\n*\"The Toothless Terror\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Scylla (98)|HMS ''Scylla'']]'''\n*\"Toasted O\" \u2013 '''[[USS Oriskany (CV-34)|USS ''Oriskany'']]'''\n*\"Traffie\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Trafalgar (1887)|HMS ''Trafalgar'']]'''\n*\"Trawler Mauler\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Nipigon (DDH 266)|HMCS ''Nipigon'']]''' \u2013 stems from an incident in the late 1980s when ''Nipigon'' sank a civilian fishing trawler for being a hazard to shipping\n*\"Tullibeast\" \u2013 '''[[USS Tullibee (SSN-597)|USS ''Tullibee'']]'''\n*\"The Tartan Terror\" \u2013 '''[[HMAS Stuart (FFH 153)|HMAS ''Stuart'']]'''\n*\"Tottenham\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Hotspur (H01)|HMS ''Hotspur'']]'''. After [[association football|football]] team [[Tottenham Hotspur]].\n*\"Tupperware\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Wilton (M1116)|HMS ''Wilton'']]'''. First warship to be constructed from [[Glass-reinforced plastic]].\n*\"Tuska class\" \u2013 Finnish navy '''[[Tuima class missile boat]]s'''. ''Tuska'' means \"agony\" in Finnish.\n* \"Tortanic\" \u2013 '''USS ''Tortuga'' (LSD-46)'''\n* \"Top Gun\" \u2013 '''USS ''Ranger'' (CV/CVA-61)'''\n\n==U==\n*\"Uproarious\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Glorious|HMS ''Glorious'']]'''<ref>[http://www.royal-navy.org/shiplist/index.php?option=com_content&task=section&id=5&Itemid=13]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==V==\n*\"VDQ\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Ville de Qu\u00e9bec (FFH 332)|NCSM ''Ville de Qu\u00e9bec'']]'''. Note that as a designated French-language unit, she properly uses the title ''Navire canadien de Sa Majest\u00e9'' (NCSM), which is the French translation of ''Her Majesty's Canadian Ship'' (HMCS)).\n*\"Von Stupid\" \u2013 '''[[USS Von Steuben (SSBN-632)|USS ''Von Steuben'']]'''\n*\"Vince\" \u2013 '''[[HMS Invincible (R05)|HMS ''Invincible]]'''''\n*\"Vinny\" \u2013 '''{{USS|Vincennes|CA-44}}'''''\n\n==W==\n* \"Weavy\" \u2013 '''[[USS West Virginia (BB-48)|USS ''West Virginia'']]'''\n* \"Wet Ass Queen\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Wetaskiwin (K175)|HMCS ''Wetaskiwin'']]'''<ref>[http://www.battleships-cruisers.co.uk/canadian_navy.htm]</ref>\n* \"Winter Pig\" \u2013 '''[[HMCS Winnipeg (FFH 338)|HMCS ''Winnipeg'']]'''\n* \"Wisky\" \u2013 '''[[USS Wisconsin (BB-64)|USS ''Wisconsin'']]'''\n* \"Wicked Witch of the West\" - '''[[USS Wichita (AOR-1)| USS ''Wichita'']]'''\n\n==X==\n{{Empty section|date=October 2010}}\n\n==Y==\n\n* \"The Y\" \u2013 '''[[USS Yakutat (AVP-32)|USCGC ''Yakutat'']]'''\n\n==Z==\n*\"Zippo\" \u2013 '''[[USS Forrestal (CVA-59)|USS ''Forrestal'']]'''<ref>[http://unitpages.military.com/unitpages/unit.do?id=200205]</ref>\n*\"Zoo (The) \u2013 '''[[USS Kalamazoo (AOR-6)|USS ''Kalamazoo'']]'''\n\n==Abbreviations==\n*'''NCSM''' \u2013 \"Navire canadien de Sa Majest\u00e9\"; applied to [[Royal Canadian Navy]] and [[Canadian Forces]] vessels designated as French-language units.\n*'''HMAS''' \u2013 \"His/Her Majesty's Australian Ship\"; applied to [[Royal Australian Navy]] vessels\n*'''HMCS''' \u2013 \"His/Her Majesty's Canadian Ship\"; applied to [[Royal Canadian Navy]] and [[Canadian Forces]] vessels\n*'''HMNZS''' \u2013 \"His/Her Majesty's New Zealand Ship\"; applied to [[Royal New Zealand Navy]] vessels\n*'''HMS''' \u2013 \"His/Her Majesty's Ship\"; applied to [[Royal Navy]] vessels\n*'''USS''' \u2013 \"United States Ship\"; applied to [[United States Navy]] vessels\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Lists}}\n* [[List of nicknames of British Army regiments]]\n* [[Lists of nicknames]] \u2013 nickname list articles on Wikipedia\n* [[Nicknames of U.S. Army divisions]]\n* [[Regimental nicknames of the Canadian Forces]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of nicknames|Warships]]\n", "name_user": "Chrism", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eD", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_warships_by_nickname"}
{"title_page": "Christopher Ward (British politician)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Christopher Ward}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n'''Christopher John Ferguson Ward''' (born 26 December 1942) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[solicitor]] and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician, who served as a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for only seven months after winning a byelection. His attempts to be selected for a safe seat were thwarted, and when he found a winnable marginal seat, he found his vote split by an unofficial Conservative candidate.\n\n== Education ==\nWard was educated at [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]] in [[Oxford]], and then at the [[Law Society]] School of Law;<ref name=\"Who's Who\">\"Who's Who\", A & C Black.</ref> he was admitted to the roll of [[solicitor]]s in January 1965.<ref name=\"Roll of solicitors\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lawsociety.org.uk:80/choosingandusing/findasolicitor/view=solicitordetails.law?id=93826&orgid=330641&SURNAME=ward&FORENAMES=&FIRMNAME=&POSTCODE=&searchType=S |title=Law Society Roll of Solicitors |accessdate=2007-12-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927165736/http://www.lawsociety.org.uk/choosingandusing/findasolicitor/view=solicitordetails.law?id=93826&orgid=330641&SURNAME=ward&FORENAMES=&FIRMNAME=&POSTCODE=&searchType=S |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was employed a solicitor in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]].<ref name=\"Byelection candidate\">\"Five by-elections on October 30\", ''The Times'', 14 October 1969, p. 1.</ref>\n\n== County councillor ==\nWard was already committed to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and was elected Chairman of the [[Young Conservatives (UK)|Young Conservatives]] in the Wessex area.<ref name=\"Christchurch and Lymington selection\">\"The Times Diary\", ''The Times'', 6 May 1972, p. 14.</ref> In 1965 Ward began his political career when he was elected to [[Berkshire County Council]]. He became chairman of the Road Safety committee and in February 1969 he condemned the state of the [[A4 road (Great Britain)|A4]] between [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] and [[Hungerford]] as a \"killer road\", after 38 people were killed on the road in the space of eighteen months.<ref name=\"A4 road safety\">Geoffrey Charles, \"New speed limits on the way\", ''The Times'', 26 February 1969, p. 4.</ref>\n\n== By-election campaign ==\nWhen [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Francis Noel-Baker]] [[resignation from the British House of Commons|resigned]] from the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in 1969, Ward was selected as the Conservative candidate in the [[1969 Swindon by-election|resulting by-election]].<ref name=\"Byelection candidate\" /> Ward noted the large number of candidates (the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], [[Communist Party of Great Britain]] and a \"Young Socialist\" candidate stood) could help him win if disenchanted Labour voters stayed at home.<ref name=\"Byelection campaign\">Denis Taylor, \"Liberals hopeful at Swindon\", ''The Times'', 23 October 1969, p. 10.</ref> After a recount, Ward won with a majority of 478, overturning Noel-Baker's majority of over 10,000 at the [[1966 United Kingdom general election|1966 general election]]; his victory speech was received in hostility by a Labour-supporting crowd.<ref name=\"Byelection victory\">Tim Jones, \"Winner is shouted down\", ''The Times'', 31 October 1969, p. 1.</ref>\n\n== Parliament ==\nWard made his [[maiden speech]] in a debate on [[Capital punishment in the United Kingdom|capital punishment]] in December 1969, declaring that he wanted to vote for abolition of the death penalty with a clear conscience but that there was inadequate evidence that it was safe to do so.<ref name=\"Maiden speech\">\"Mr Hogg predicts hanging will be election issue: censure rejected by 62 votes\", ''The Times'', 16 December 1969, p. 4.</ref> In January 1970 he initiated a debate on housebuilding, insisting that half a million houses needed to be built every year in order to solve the housing problem; he called on the Labour government to apologise for failing to meet that target.<ref name=\"Housebuilding\">\"Housing achievement still best - Minister\", ''The Times'', 28 January 1970, p. 4.</ref>\n\n== Defeat ==\nAt the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|general election in June 1970]], Ward tried to attract attention by campaigning on a horse and cart.<ref name=\"1970 campaign\">[[David Butler (academic)|David Butler]] and Michael Pinto-Duschinsky, \"The British General Election of 1970\" (Macmillan, 1970), p. 321.</ref> However, he could not prevent the Labour candidate [[David Stoddart, Baron Stoddart of Swindon|David Stoddart]] retaking the seat with a majority of 5,576.<ref name=\"Times Guide 1970\">\"The Times Guide to the House of Commons, 1970\", p. 213.</ref>\n\n== Selections ==\nWard began to look round for a winnable constituency to fight, and was considered for the [[Arundel and Shoreham (UK Parliament constituency)|Arundel and Shoreham]] constituency in a [[1971 Arundel and Shoreham by-election|1971 byelection]].<ref name=\"Arundel and Shoreham\">\"The Times Diary\", ''The Times'', 6 February 1971, p. 12.</ref> In 1972 he was shortlisted for [[Mid Oxfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Oxon]], losing out to [[Douglas Hurd]],<ref name=\"Mid Oxon selection\">\"The Times Diary\", ''The Times'', 22 January 1972, p. 12.</ref> and for [[Kingston-upon-Thames (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston-upon-Thames]], losing out to [[Norman Lamont (1942)|Norman Lamont]]; he was perceived as being on the left of the Conservative Party.<ref name=\"Kingston-upon-Thames selection\">\"The Times Diary\", ''The Times'', 4 February 1972, p. 12.</ref> He was also edged out at [[Christchurch and Lymington (UK Parliament constituency)|Christchurch and Lymington]] by [[Robert Adley]],<ref name=\"Christchurch and Lymington selection\" /> at [[Beaconsfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Beaconsfield]] by [[Ronald Bell (UK politician)|Ronald Bell]],<ref name=\"Beaconsfield selection\">\"The Times Diary\", ''The Times'', 13 June 1972, p. 14.</ref> and at [[Hove (UK Parliament constituency)|Hove]] by [[Tim Sainsbury]].<ref name=\"Hove selection\">\"Two former MPs on Tory short list for Hove\", ''The Times'', 1 October 1973, p. 2.</ref> Ward was ultimately not selected anywhere in the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February]] and [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 general elections]].\n\n== Eton and Slough candidate ==\nWard had stood down from Berkshire County Council in 1970 but returned to it in 1974; he served as Deputy Leader and chair of the Finance sub-committee. He was also a member of the South East Regional Planning Council.<ref name=\"Times Guide 1979\">\"The Times Guide to the House of Commons, 1979\", p. 109.</ref> He had better luck with Parliamentary selections in 1976 when he was chosen as Conservative candidate for [[Eton and Slough (UK Parliament constituency)|Eton and Slough]]. At the 1976 Conservative Party conference, Ward opened the discussion on \"People, Parliament and the Constitution\", arguing that Britain was no longer a truly free society because the Labour government wanted a state-controlled society.<ref name=\"Party conference speech 1976\">\"Lord Carrington rejects Government's devolution plan for Scotland and Wales\", ''The Times'', 8 October 1976, p. 6.</ref>\n\nAt the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 general election]], Ward faced an additional challenge when a rebel local Conservative councillor who had recently served as Mayor was nominated as an unofficial candidate.<ref name=\"1979 election\">David Butler and Denis Kavanagh, \"The British General Election of 1979\" (Macmillan, 1979), p. 421.</ref> Ward ended up losing the election by 1,340 votes with the unofficial candidate taking 2,359 votes.<ref name=\"Times Guide 1979\" />\n\n== Later career ==\nLater in 1979, Ward became Leader of Berkshire County Council (Chairman of the Policy Committee); he served until 1981 when the Conservatives lost control. He was a Governor of Chiltern Nursery Training College from 1975 to 1997, serving as Chairman in 1988\u201391; he also served London Conservative clubland as hon. Secretary of the [[United and Cecil Club]] from 1982 to 1987, and became club Treasurer in 1993.<ref name=\"Who's Who\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of United Kingdom MPs with the shortest service]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-christopher-ward | Christopher Ward  }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Swindon (UK Parliament constituency)|Swindon]]\n  | years  = [[1969 Swindon by-election|1969]]\u2013[[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970]]\n  | before = [[Francis Noel-Baker]]\n  | after  = [[David Stoddart, Baron Stoddart of Swindon|David Stoddart]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ward, Christopher}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1966\u20131970]]\n[[Category:Members of Berkshire County Council]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Christopher Ward}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n'''Christopher John Ferguson Ward''' (born 26 December 1942) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[solicitor]] and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician, who served as a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for only seven months after winning a byelection. His attempts to be selected for a safe seat were thwarted, and when he found a winnable marginal seat, he found his vote split by an unofficial Conservative candidate.\n\n== Education ==\nWard was educated at [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]] in [[Oxford]], and then at the [[Law Society]] School of Law;<ref name=\"Who's Who\">\"Who's Who\", A & C Black.</ref> he was admitted to the roll of [[solicitor]]s in January 1965.<ref name=\"Roll of solicitors\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lawsociety.org.uk:80/choosingandusing/findasolicitor/view=solicitordetails.law?id=93826&orgid=330641&SURNAME=ward&FORENAMES=&FIRMNAME=&POSTCODE=&searchType=S |title=Law Society Roll of Solicitors |accessdate=2007-12-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927165736/http://www.lawsociety.org.uk/choosingandusing/findasolicitor/view=solicitordetails.law?id=93826&orgid=330641&SURNAME=ward&FORENAMES=&FIRMNAME=&POSTCODE=&searchType=S |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was employed a solicitor in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]].<ref name=\"Byelection candidate\">\"Five by-elections on October 30\", ''The Times'', 14 October 1969, p. 1.</ref>\n\n== County councillor ==\nWard was already committed to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and was elected Chairman of the [[Young Conservatives (UK)|Young Conservatives]] in the Wessex area.<ref name=\"Christchurch and Lymington selection\">\"The Times Diary\", ''The Times'', 6 May 1972, p. 14.</ref> In 1965 Ward began his political career when he was elected to [[Berkshire County Council]]. He became chairman of the Road Safety committee and in February 1969 he condemned the state of the [[A4 road (Great Britain)|A4]] between [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] and [[Hungerford]] as a \"killer road\", after 38 people were killed on the road in the space of eighteen months.<ref name=\"A4 road safety\">Geoffrey Charles, \"New speed limits on the way\", ''The Times'', 26 February 1969, p. 4.</ref>\n\n== By-election campaign ==\nWhen [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Francis Noel-Baker]] [[resignation from the British House of Commons|resigned]] from the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in 1969, Ward was selected as the Conservative candidate in the [[1969 Swindon by-election|resulting by-election]].<ref name=\"Byelection candidate\" /> Ward noted the large number of candidates (the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], [[Communist Party of Great Britain]] and a \"Young Socialist\" candidate stood) could help him win if disenchanted Labour voters stayed at home.<ref name=\"Byelection campaign\">Denis Taylor, \"Liberals hopeful at Swindon\", ''The Times'', 23 October 1969, p. 10.</ref> After a recount, Ward won with a majority of 478, overturning Noel-Baker's majority of over 10,000 at the [[1966 United Kingdom general election|1966 general election]]; his victory speech was received in hostility by a Labour-supporting crowd.<ref name=\"Byelection victory\">Tim Jones, \"Winner is shouted down\", ''The Times'', 31 October 1969, p. 1.</ref>\n\n== Parliament ==\nWard made his [[maiden speech]] in a debate on [[Capital punishment in the United Kingdom|capital punishment]] in December 1969, declaring that he wanted to vote for abolition of the death penalty with a clear conscience but that there was inadequate evidence that it was safe to do so.<ref name=\"Maiden speech\">\"Mr Hogg predicts hanging will be election issue: censure rejected by 62 votes\", ''The Times'', 16 December 1969, p. 4.</ref> In January 1970 he initiated a debate on housebuilding, insisting that half a million houses needed to be built every year in order to solve the housing problem; he called on the Labour government to apologise for failing to meet that target.<ref name=\"Housebuilding\">\"Housing achievement still best - Minister\", ''The Times'', 28 January 1970, p. 4.</ref>\n\n== Defeat ==\nAt the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|general election in June 1970]], Ward tried to attract attention by campaigning on a horse and cart.<ref name=\"1970 campaign\">[[David Butler (academic)|David Butler]] and Michael Pinto-Duschinsky, \"The British General Election of 1970\" (Macmillan, 1970), p. 321.</ref> However, he could not prevent the Labour candidate [[David Stoddart, Baron Stoddart of Swindon|David Stoddart]] retaking the seat with a majority of 5,576.<ref name=\"Times Guide 1970\">\"The Times Guide to the House of Commons, 1970\", p. 213.</ref>\n\n== Selections ==\nWard began to look round for a winnable constituency to fight, and was considered for the [[Arundel and Shoreham (UK Parliament constituency)|Arundel and Shoreham]] constituency in a [[1971 Arundel and Shoreham by-election|1971 byelection]].<ref name=\"Arundel and Shoreham\">\"The Times Diary\", ''The Times'', 6 February 1971, p. 12.</ref> In 1972 he was shortlisted for [[Mid Oxfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Oxon]], losing out to [[Douglas Hurd]],<ref name=\"Mid Oxon selection\">\"The Times Diary\", ''The Times'', 22 January 1972, p. 12.</ref> and for [[Kingston-upon-Thames (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston-upon-Thames]], losing out to [[Norman Lamont (1942)|Norman Lamont]]; he was perceived as being on the left of the Conservative Party.<ref name=\"Kingston-upon-Thames selection\">\"The Times Diary\", ''The Times'', 4 February 1972, p. 12.</ref> He was also edged out at [[Christchurch and Lymington (UK Parliament constituency)|Christchurch and Lymington]] by [[Robert Adley]],<ref name=\"Christchurch and Lymington selection\" /> at [[Beaconsfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Beaconsfield]] by [[Ronald Bell (UK politician)|Ronald Bell]],<ref name=\"Beaconsfield selection\">\"The Times Diary\", ''The Times'', 13 June 1972, p. 14.</ref> and at [[Hove (UK Parliament constituency)|Hove]] by [[Tim Sainsbury]].<ref name=\"Hove selection\">\"Two former MPs on Tory short list for Hove\", ''The Times'', 1 October 1973, p. 2.</ref> Ward was ultimately not selected anywhere in the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February]] and [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 general elections]].\n\n== Eton and Slough candidate ==\nWard had stood down from Berkshire County Council in 1970 but returned to it in 1974; he served as Deputy Leader and chair of the Finance sub-committee. He was also a member of the South East Regional Planning Council.<ref name=\"Times Guide 1979\">\"The Times Guide to the House of Commons, 1979\", p. 109.</ref> He had better luck with Parliamentary selections in 1976 when he was chosen as Conservative candidate for [[Eton and Slough (UK Parliament constituency)|Eton and Slough]]. At the 1976 Conservative Party conference, Ward opened the discussion on \"People, Parliament and the Constitution\", arguing that Britain was no longer a truly free society because the Labour government wanted a state-controlled society.<ref name=\"Party conference speech 1976\">\"Lord Carrington rejects Government's devolution plan for Scotland and Wales\", ''The Times'', 8 October 1976, p. 6.</ref>\n\nAt the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 general election]], Ward faced an additional challenge when a rebel local Conservative councillor who had recently served as Mayor was nominated as an unofficial candidate.<ref name=\"1979 election\">David Butler and Denis Kavanagh, \"The British General Election of 1979\" (Macmillan, 1979), p. 421.</ref> Ward ended up losing the election by 1,340 votes with the unofficial candidate taking 2,359 votes.<ref name=\"Times Guide 1979\" />\n\n== Later career ==\nLater in 1979, Ward became Leader of Berkshire County Council (Chairman of the Policy Committee); he served until 1981 when the Conservatives lost control. He was a Governor of Chiltern Nursery Training College from 1975 to 1997, serving as Chairman in 1988-91; he also served London Conservative clubland as hon. Secretary of the [[United and Cecil Club]] from 1982 to 1987, and became club Treasurer in 1993.<ref name=\"Who's Who\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of United Kingdom MPs with the shortest service]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-christopher-ward | Christopher Ward  }}\n\n{{s-start}}